# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermodynamicist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In thermodynamics, **heat** is defined as energy in transfer between a body and its surroundings, other than through thermodynamic work or through transfer of matter.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Rather than by mechanical or other effects in the surroundings, thermodynamic work is defined through changes in the system’s macroscopic state variables, in conjugate pairs such as pressure and volume, or magnetisation and magnetic field strength.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The thermodynamic definition of heat is by exclusion of other defined modes of transfer in order to ensure a strict logical distinction.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In the process of transfer, heat is not necessarily conserved, but can be generated (though not destroyed) by friction.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In thermodynamics, temperature is defined in macroscopic terms, through the concepts of heat and work.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat is not a state variable or state function; it is a process quantity.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A thermodynamic system does not *contain* heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat can enter or leave a body of matter by thermal conduction, by electromagnetic radiation, or through friction due to macroscopic mechanical movement.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] When heat is generated by friction, it may end up partly in each of the two engaged bodies.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] When energy enters or leaves a body through transfer of matter, it cannot be resolved uniquely into work and heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] By assuming conservation of heat in a transfer, calorimetry measures it by its effect on the states of interacting bodies, for example, by the amount of ice melted or by change in temperature of a body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In the International System of Units (SI), the unit of measurement for heat is the joule (J).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] As a form of energy, heat has the unit joule (J) in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In addition, many applied branches of engineering use other, traditional units, such as the British thermal unit (BTU) and the calorie.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The standard unit for the rate of heating is the watt (W), defined as one joule per second.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The symbol Q for heat was introduced by Rudolf Clausius and Macquorn Rankine in c.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat released by a system into its surroundings is by convention, as a contributor to internal energy, a negative quantity (*Q* < 0); when a system absorbs heat from its surroundings, it is positive (*Q* > 0).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat transfer rate, or heat flow per unit time, is denoted by ${\dot {Q}}$ , but it is not a time derivative of a function of state (which can also be written with the dot notation) since heat is not a function of state.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat flux is defined as rate of heat transfer per unit cross-sectional area (watts per square metre).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In ordinary language, English 'heat' or 'warmth', just as French *chaleur*, German *Hitze* or *Wärme*, Latin *calor*, Greek θάλπος, etc. refers to either thermal energy or temperature, or the human perception of these.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Later, *chaleur* (as used by Sadi Carnot), 'heat', and *Wärme* became equivalents also as specific scientific terms at an early stage of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Speculation on 'heat' as a separate form of matter has a long history, involving the phlogiston theory, the caloric theory, and fire.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Many careful and accurate historical experiments practically exclude friction, mechanical and thermodynamic work and matter transfer, investigating transfer of energy only by thermal conduction and radiation.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Such experiments give impressive rational support to the caloric theory of heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] To account also for changes of internal energy due to friction, and mechanical and thermodynamic work, the caloric theory was, around the end of the eighteenth century, replaced by the "mechanical" theory of heat, which is accepted today.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] As scientists of the early modern age began to adopt the view that matter consists of particles, a close relationship between heat and the motion of those particles was widely surmised, or even the equivalency of the concepts, boldly expressed by the English philosopher Francis Bacon in 1620.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Galileo wrote that heat and pressure are apparent properties only, caused by the movement of particles, which is a real phenomenon.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1665, and again in 1681, English polymath Robert Hooke reiterated that heat is nothing but the motion of the constituent particles of objects, and in 1675, his colleague, Anglo-Irish scientist Robert Boyle repeated that this motion is what heat consists of.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat has been discussed in ordinary language by philosophers.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] When Bacon, Galileo, Hooke, Boyle and Locke wrote "heat", they might more have referred to what we would now call "temperature".
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] No clear distinction was made between heat and temperature until the mid-18th century, nor between the internal energy of a body and the transfer of energy as heat until the mid-19th century.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Locke's description of heat was repeatedly quoted by English physicist James Prescott Joule.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Also the transfer of heat was explained by the motion of particles.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The theory was developed in academic publications in French, English and German.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Unstated distinctions between heat and “hotness” may be very old, heat seen as something dependent on the *quantity* of a hot substance, “heat”, vaguely perhaps distinct from the *quality* of "hotness".
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1723, the English mathematician Brook Taylor measured the temperature—the expansion of the liquid in a thermometer—of mixtures of various amounts of hot water in cold water.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] As expected, the increase in temperature was in proportion to the proportion of hot water in the mixture.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The distinction between heat and temperature is implicitly expressed in the last sentence of his report.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1748, an account was published in *The Edinburgh Physical and Literary Essays* of an experiment by the Scottish physician and chemist William Cullen.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Cullen had used an air pump to lower the pressure in a container with diethyl ether.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The ether boiled, while no heat was withdrawn from it, and its temperature decreased.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] And in 1758 on a warm day in Cambridge, England, Benjamin Franklin and fellow scientist John Hadley experimented by continually wetting the ball of a mercury thermometer with ether and using bellows to evaporate the ether.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] With each subsequent evaporation, the thermometer read a lower temperature, eventually reaching 7 °F (−14 °C).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1756 or soon thereafter, Joseph Black, Cullen’s friend and former assistant, began an extensive study of heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1760 Black realized that when two different substances of equal mass but different temperatures are mixed, the changes in number of degrees in the two substances differ, though the heat gained by the cooler substance and lost by the hotter is the same.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Black related an experiment conducted by Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit on behalf of Dutch physician Herman Boerhaave.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This clarified the distinction between heat and temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It also introduced the concept of specific heat capacity, being different for different substances.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In his investigations of specific heat, Black used a unit of heat he called "degrees of heat"—as opposed to just "degrees" [of temperature].
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This unit was context-dependent and could only be used when circumstances were identical.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It was based on change in temperature multiplied by the mass of the substance involved.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It was known that when the air temperature rises above freezing—air then becoming the obvious heat source—snow melts very slowly and the temperature of the melted snow is close to its freezing point.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1757, Black started to investigate if heat, therefore, was required for the melting of a solid, independent of any rise in temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] As far Black knew, the general view at that time was that melting was inevitably accompanied by a small increase in temperature, and that no additional heat was needed beyond what this increase in temperature would require in itself.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Soon, however, Black was able to show that much more heat was required during melting than could be explained by any increase in temperature alone.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He was also able to show that heat is *released* by a liquid during its freezing; again, much more than could be explained by the decrease of its temperature alone.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1762, Black announced the following research and results to a society of professors at the University of Glasgow.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Black had placed equal masses of ice at 32 °F (0 °C) and water at 33 °F (0.6 °C) respectively in two identical, well separated containers.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The water and the ice were both evenly heated to 40 °F by the air in the room, which was at a constant 47 °F (8 °C).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The water had therefore received 40 – 33 = 7 “degrees of heat”.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The ice had been heated for 21 times longer and had therefore received 7 × 21 = 147 “degrees of heat”.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The temperature of the ice had increased by 8 °F.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The ice had thus absorbed 8 “degrees of heat”, which Black called *sensible heat*, manifest as temperature change, which could be felt and measured.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In addition to that, 147 – 8 = 139 “degrees of heat” were absorbed as *latent heat*, manifest as phase change rather than as temperature change.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Black next showed that a water temperature of 176 °F was needed to melt an equal mass of ice until it was all 32 °F.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] So now 176 – 32 = 144 “degrees of heat” seemed to be needed to melt the ice.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The modern value for the heat of fusion of ice would be 143 “degrees of heat” on the same scale (79.5 “degrees of heat Celsius”).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Finally, Black increased the temperature of a mass of water, then vaporized an equal mass of water by even heating.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He showed that 830 “degrees of heat” was needed for the vaporization; again based on the time required.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The modern value for the heat of vaporization of water would be 967 “degrees of heat” on the same scale.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A calorimeter is a device used for measuring heat capacity, as well as the heat absorbed or released in chemical reactions or physical changes.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1780, French chemist Antoine Lavoisier used such an apparatus—which he named 'calorimeter'—to investigate the heat released by respiration, by observing how this heat melted snow surrounding his apparatus.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A so called *ice calorimeter* was used 1782–83 by Lavoisier and his colleague Pierre-Simon Laplace to measure the heat released in various chemical reactions.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The heat so released melted a specific amount of ice, and the heat required for the melting of a certain amount of ice was known beforehand.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The modern understanding of heat is often partly attributed to Thompson's 1798 mechanical theory of heat ("An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction"), postulating a mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A collaboration between Nicolas Clément and Sadi Carnot (*Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire*) in the 1820s had some related thinking along similar lines.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In 1842, Julius Robert Mayer frictionally generated heat in paper pulp and measured the temperature rise.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The theory of classical thermodynamics matured in the 1850s to 1860s.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The process function Q was introduced by Rudolf Clausius in 1850.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Clausius described it with the German compound *Wärmemenge*, translated as "amount of heat".
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Bryan published an investigation of the foundations of thermodynamics, *Thermodynamics: an Introductory Treatise dealing mainly with First Principles and their Direct Applications*, B.G.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Bryan was writing when thermodynamics had been established empirically, but people were still interested to specify its logical structure.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The 1909 work of Carathéodory also belongs to this historical era.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Bryan was a physicist while Carathéodory was a mathematician.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Bryan started his treatise with an introductory chapter on the notions of heat and of temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He gives an example of where the notion of heating as raising a body's temperature contradicts the notion of heating as imparting a quantity of heat to that body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He defined an adiabatic transformation as one in which the body neither gains nor loses heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This is not the same as defining an adiabatic transformation as one that occurs to a body enclosed by walls impermeable to radiation and conduction.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He recognized calorimetry as a way of measuring quantity of heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He recognized water as having a *temperature of maximum density*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This makes water unsuitable as a thermometric substance around that temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He intended to remind readers of why thermodynamicists preferred an absolute scale of temperature, independent of the properties of a particular thermometric substance.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] His second chapter started with the recognition of friction as a source of heat, by Benjamin Thompson, by Humphry Davy, by Robert Mayer, and by James Prescott Joule.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] When heat is transformed into work or conversely work is transformed into heat, the quantity of heat gained or lost is proportional to the quantity of work lost or gained.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] If heat be measured in dynamical units the mechanical equivalent becomes equal to unity, and the equations of thermodynamics assume a simpler and more symmetrical form.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He explained how the caloric theory of Lavoisier and Laplace made sense in terms of pure calorimetry, though it failed to account for conversion of work into heat by such mechanisms as friction and conduction of electricity.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Having rationally defined quantity of heat, he went on to consider the second law, including the Kelvin definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Physical unreality of reversible processes.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In Nature all phenomena are irreversible in a greater or less degree.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In §47, on page 39, he stated the principle of conservation of energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In connection with irreversible phenomena the following axioms have to be assumed.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A perfectly reversible change cannot take place of itself; such a change can only be regarded as the limiting form of an irreversible change.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] When two bodies act thermically on one another the quantities of heat gained by one and lost by the other are not necessarily equal.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In the case of bodies at a distance, heat may be taken from or given to the intervening medium.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Another important exception occurs when sliding takes place between two rough bodies in contact.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The algebraic sum of the works done is different from zero, because, although the action and reaction are equal and opposite the velocities of the parts of the bodies in contact are different.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Moreover, the work lost in the process does not increase the mutual potential energy of the system and there is no intervening medium between the bodies.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Unless the lost energy can be accounted for in other ways, (as when friction produces electrification), it follows from the Principle of Conservation of Energy that the algebraic sum of the quantities of heat gained by the two systems is equal to the quantity of work lost by friction.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This thought was echoed in some detail in 1941 by Bridgman.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A celebrated and frequent definition of heat in thermodynamics is based on the work of Carathéodory (1909), referring to processes in a closed system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Carathéodory was responding to a suggestion by Max Born that he examine the logical structure of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The internal energy *UX* of a body in an arbitrary state *X* can be determined by amounts of work adiabatically performed by the body on its surroundings when it starts from a reference state *O*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Such work is assessed through quantities defined in the surroundings of the body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is supposed that such work can be assessed accurately, without error due to friction in the surroundings; friction in the body is not excluded by this definition.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The adiabatic performance of work is defined in terms of adiabatic walls, which allow transfer of energy as work, but no other transfer, of energy or matter.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In particular they do not allow the passage of energy as heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] According to this definition, work performed adiabatically is in general accompanied by friction within the thermodynamic system or body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] On the other hand, according to Carathéodory (1909), there also exist non-adiabatic, *diathermal* walls, which are postulated to be permeable only to heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] For the definition of quantity of energy transferred as heat, it is customarily envisaged that an arbitrary state of interest *Y* is reached from state *O* by a process with two components, one adiabatic and the other not adiabatic.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] For convenience one may say that the adiabatic component was the sum of work done by the body through volume change through movement of the walls while the non-adiabatic wall was temporarily rendered adiabatic, and of isochoric adiabatic work.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Then the non-adiabatic component is a process of energy transfer through the wall that passes only heat, newly made accessible for the purpose of this transfer, from the surroundings to the body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The change in internal energy to reach the state *Y* from the state *O* is the difference of the two amounts of energy transferred.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In this definition, for the sake of conceptual rigour, the quantity of energy transferred as heat is not specified directly in terms of the non-adiabatic process.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is defined through knowledge of precisely two variables, the change of internal energy and the amount of adiabatic work done, for the combined process of change from the reference state *O* to the arbitrary state *Y*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is important that this does not explicitly involve the amount of energy transferred in the non-adiabatic component of the combined process.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is assumed here that the amount of energy required to pass from state *O* to state *Y*, the change of internal energy, is known, independently of the combined process, by a determination through a purely adiabatic process, like that for the determination of the internal energy of state *X* above.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The rigour that is prized in this definition is that there is one and only one kind of energy transfer admitted as fundamental: energy transferred as work.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Energy transfer as heat is considered as a derived quantity.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The uniqueness of work in this scheme is considered to guarantee rigor and purity of conception.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The conceptual purity of this definition, based on the concept of energy transferred as work as an ideal notion, relies on the idea that some frictionless and otherwise non-dissipative processes of energy transfer can be realized in physical actuality.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The second law of thermodynamics, on the other hand, assures us that such processes are not found in nature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Before the rigorous mathematical definition of heat based on Carathéodory's 1909 paper, historically, heat, temperature, and thermal equilibrium were presented in thermodynamics textbooks as jointly primitive notions.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] That heat is an appropriate and natural primitive for thermodynamics was already accepted by Carnot.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is sometimes proposed that this traditional kind of presentation necessarily rests on "circular reasoning".
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This alternative approach to the definition of quantity of energy transferred as heat differs in logical structure from that of Carathéodory, recounted just above.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This alternative approach admits calorimetry as a primary or direct way to measure quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It relies on temperature as one of its primitive concepts, and used in calorimetry.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is presupposed that enough processes exist physically to allow measurement of differences in internal energies.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Such processes are not restricted to adiabatic transfers of energy as work.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] They include calorimetry, which is the commonest practical way of finding internal energy differences.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The needed temperature can be either empirical or absolute thermodynamic.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In contrast, the Carathéodory way recounted just above does not use calorimetry or temperature in its primary definition of quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The Carathéodory way regards calorimetry only as a secondary or indirect way of measuring quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] As recounted in more detail just above, the Carathéodory way regards quantity of energy transferred as heat in a process as primarily or directly defined as a residual quantity.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is calculated from the difference of the internal energies of the initial and final states of the system, and from the actual work done by the system during the process.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] That internal energy difference is supposed to have been measured in advance through processes of purely adiabatic transfer of energy as work, processes that take the system between the initial and final states.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] By the Carathéodory way it is presupposed as known from experiment that there actually physically exist enough such adiabatic processes, so that there need be no recourse to calorimetry for measurement of quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This presupposition is essential but is explicitly labeled neither as a law of thermodynamics nor as an axiom of the Carathéodory way.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In fact, the actual physical existence of such adiabatic processes is indeed mostly supposition, and those supposed processes have in most cases not been actually verified empirically to exist.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Over the years, for example in his 1879 thesis, but particularly in 1926, Planck advocated regarding the generation of heat by rubbing as the most specific way to define heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Planck criticised Carathéodory for not attending to this.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Carathéodory was a mathematician who liked to think in terms of adiabatic processes, and perhaps found friction too tricky to think about, while Planck was a physicist.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Maxwell writes that convection as such "is not a purely thermal phenomenon".
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In thermodynamics, convection in general is regarded as transport of internal energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] If, however, the convection is enclosed and circulatory, then it may be regarded as an intermediary that transfers energy as heat between source and destination bodies, because it transfers only energy and not matter from the source to the destination body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In accordance with the first law for closed systems, energy transferred solely as heat leaves one body and enters another, changing the internal energies of each.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Transfer, between bodies, of energy as work is a complementary way of changing internal energies.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Though it is not logically rigorous from the viewpoint of strict physical concepts, a common form of words that expresses this is to say that heat and work are interconvertible.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Cyclically operating engines that use only heat and work transfers have two thermal reservoirs, a hot and a cold one.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] They may be classified by the range of operating temperatures of the working body, relative to those reservoirs.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In a heat engine, the working body is at all times colder than the hot reservoir and hotter than the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In a sense, it uses heat transfer to produce work.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In a heat pump, the working body, at stages of the cycle, goes both hotter than the hot reservoir, and colder than the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In a sense, it uses work to produce heat transfer.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In classical thermodynamics, a commonly considered model is the heat engine.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It consists of four bodies: the working body, the hot reservoir, the cold reservoir, and the work reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A cyclic process leaves the working body in an unchanged state, and is envisaged as being repeated indefinitely often.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Work transfers between the working body and the work reservoir are envisaged as reversible, and thus only one work reservoir is needed.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] But two thermal reservoirs are needed, because transfer of energy as heat is irreversible.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A single cycle sees energy taken by the working body from the hot reservoir and sent to the two other reservoirs, the work reservoir and the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The hot reservoir always and only supplies energy, and the cold reservoir always and only receives energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that no cycle can occur in which no energy is received by the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat engines achieve higher efficiency when the ratio of the initial and final temperature is greater.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Another commonly considered model is the heat pump or refrigerator.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Again there are four bodies: the working body, the hot reservoir, the cold reservoir, and the work reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A single cycle starts with the working body colder than the cold reservoir, and then energy is taken in as heat by the working body from the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Then the work reservoir does work on the working body, adding more to its internal energy, making it hotter than the hot reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The hot working body passes heat to the hot reservoir, but still remains hotter than the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Then, by allowing it to expand without passing heat to another body, the working body is made colder than the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It can now accept heat transfer from the cold reservoir to start another cycle.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The device has transported energy from a colder to a hotter reservoir, but this is not regarded as by an inanimate agency; rather, it is regarded as by the harnessing of work .
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This is because work is supplied from the work reservoir, not just by a simple thermodynamic process, but by a cycle of thermodynamic operations and processes, which may be regarded as directed by an animate or harnessing agency.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Accordingly, the cycle is still in accord with the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The 'efficiency' of a heat pump (which exceeds unity) is best when the temperature difference between the hot and cold reservoirs is least.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Functionally, such engines are used in two ways, distinguishing a target reservoir and a resource or surrounding reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A heat pump transfers heat to the hot reservoir as the target from the resource or surrounding reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A refrigerator transfers heat, from the cold reservoir as the target, to the resource or surrounding reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The target reservoir may be regarded as leaking: when the target leaks heat to the surroundings, heat pumping is used; when the target leaks coldness to the surroundings, refrigeration is used.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The engines harness work to overcome the leaks.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] According to Planck, there are three main conceptual approaches to heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] One is the microscopic or kinetic theory approach.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The other two are macroscopic approaches.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] One of the macroscopic approaches is through the law of conservation of energy taken as prior to thermodynamics, with a mechanical analysis of processes, for example in the work of Helmholtz.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This mechanical view is taken in this article as currently customary for thermodynamic theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The other macroscopic approach is the thermodynamic one, which admits heat as a primitive concept, which contributes, by scientific induction to knowledge of the law of conservation of energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This view is widely taken as the practical one, quantity of heat being measured by calorimetry.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Bailyn also distinguishes the two macroscopic approaches as the mechanical and the thermodynamic.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The thermodynamic view was taken by the founders of thermodynamics in the nineteenth century.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It regards quantity of energy transferred as heat as a primitive concept coherent with a primitive concept of temperature, measured primarily by calorimetry.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A calorimeter is a body in the surroundings of the system, with its own temperature and internal energy; when it is connected to the system by a path for heat transfer, changes in it measure heat transfer.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The mechanical view was pioneered by Helmholtz and developed and used in the twentieth century, largely through the influence of Max Born.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It regards quantity of heat transferred as heat as a derived concept, defined for closed systems as quantity of heat transferred by mechanisms other than work transfer, the latter being regarded as primitive for thermodynamics, defined by macroscopic mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] According to Born, the transfer of internal energy between open systems that accompanies transfer of matter "cannot be reduced to mechanics".
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It follows that there is no well-founded definition of quantities of energy transferred as heat or as work associated with transfer of matter.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] If cross-effects that result in diffusive transfer of internal energy were also labeled as heat transfers, they would sometimes violate the rule that pure heat transfer occurs only down a temperature gradient, never up one.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] They would also contradict the principle that all heat transfer is of one and the same kind, a principle founded on the idea of heat conduction between closed systems.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In these circumstances, if perchance it happens that no transfer of matter is actualized, and there are no cross-effects, then the thermodynamic concept and the mechanical concept coincide, as if one were dealing with closed systems.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] But when there is transfer of matter, the exact laws by which temperature gradient drives diffusive flux of internal energy, rather than being exactly knowable, mostly need to be assumed, and in many cases are practically unverifiable.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Consequently, when there is transfer of matter, the calculation of the pure 'heat flux' component of the diffusive flux of internal energy rests on practically unverifiable assumptions.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This is a reason to think of heat as a specialized concept that relates primarily and precisely to closed systems, and applicable only in a very restricted way to open systems.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In many writings in this context, the term "heat flux" is used when what is meant is therefore more accurately called diffusive flux of internal energy; such usage of the term "heat flux" is a residue of older and now obsolete language usage that allowed that a body may have a "heat content".
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In the kinetic theory, heat is explained in terms of the microscopic motions and interactions of constituent particles, such as electrons, atoms, and molecules.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The immediate meaning of the kinetic energy of the constituent particles is not as heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is as a component of internal energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In microscopic terms, heat is a transfer quantity, and is described by a transport theory, not as steadily localized kinetic energy of particles.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat transfer arises from temperature gradients or differences, through the diffuse exchange of microscopic kinetic and potential particle energy, by particle collisions and other interactions.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] An early and vague expression of this was made by Francis Bacon.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Precise and detailed versions of it were developed in the nineteenth century.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is possible for macroscopic thermodynamic work to alter the occupation numbers without change in the values of the system energy levels themselves, but what distinguishes transfer as heat is that the transfer is entirely due to disordered, microscopic action, including radiative transfer.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A mathematical definition can be formulated for small increments of quasi-static adiabatic work in terms of the statistical distribution of an ensemble of microstates.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Quantity of heat transferred can be measured by calorimetry, or determined through calculations based on other quantities.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Calorimetry is the empirical basis of the idea of quantity of heat transferred in a process.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The transferred heat is measured by changes in a body of known properties, for example, temperature rise, change in volume or length, or phase change, such as melting of ice.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] A calculation of quantity of heat transferred can rely on a hypothetical quantity of energy transferred as adiabatic work and on the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Such calculation is the primary approach of many theoretical studies of quantity of heat transferred.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The discipline of heat transfer, typically considered an aspect of mechanical engineering and chemical engineering, deals with specific applied methods by which thermal energy in a system is generated, or converted, or transferred to another system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Although the definition of heat implicitly means the transfer of energy, the term *heat transfer* encompasses this traditional usage in many engineering disciplines and laymen language.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Convection may be described as the combined effects of conduction and fluid flow.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This entire process is often regarded as an additional mechanism of heat transfer, although technically, "heat transfer" and thus heating and cooling occurs only on either end of such a conductive flow, but not as a result of flow.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Thus, conduction can be said to "transfer" heat only as a net result of the process, but may not do so at every time within the complicated convective process.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In an 1847 lecture entitled *On Matter, Living Force, and Heat*, James Prescott Joule characterized the terms latent heat and sensible heat as components of heat each affecting distinct physical phenomena, namely the potential and kinetic energy of particles, respectively.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] He described latent energy as the energy possessed via a distancing of particles where attraction was over a greater distance, i.e. a form of potential energy, and the sensible heat as an energy involving the motion of particles, i.e. kinetic energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Latent heat is the heat released or absorbed by a chemical substance or a thermodynamic system during a change of state that occurs without a change in temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Such a process may be a phase transition, such as the melting of ice or the boiling of water.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat capacity is a measurable physical quantity equal to the ratio of the heat added to an object to the resulting temperature change.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The *molar heat capacity* is the heat capacity per unit amount (SI unit: mole) of a pure substance, and the *specific heat capacity*, often called simply *specific heat*, is the heat capacity per unit mass of a material.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Heat capacity is a physical property of a substance, which means that it depends on the state and properties of the substance under consideration.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The specific heats of monatomic gases, such as helium, are nearly constant with temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Diatomic gases such as hydrogen display some temperature dependence, and triatomic gases (e.g., carbon dioxide) still more.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Before the development of the laws of thermodynamics, heat was measured by changes in the states of the participating bodies.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Some general rules, with important exceptions, can be stated as follows.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In general, most bodies expand on heating.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In this circumstance, heating a body at a constant volume increases the pressure it exerts on its constraining walls, while heating at a constant pressure increases its volume.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Beyond this, most substances have three ordinarily recognized states of matter, solid, liquid, and gas.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Many have further, more finely differentiated, states of matter, such as glass and liquid crystal.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In many cases, at fixed temperature and pressure, a substance can exist in several distinct states of matter in what might be viewed as the same 'body'.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] For example, ice may float in a glass of water.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Then the ice and the water are said to constitute two phases within the 'body'.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Definite rules are known, telling how distinct phases may coexist in a 'body'.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Mostly, at a fixed pressure, there is a definite temperature at which heating causes a solid to melt or evaporate, and a definite temperature at which heating causes a liquid to evaporate.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In such cases, cooling has the reverse effects.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] All of these, the commonest cases, fit with a rule that heating can be measured by changes of state of a body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Such cases supply what are called *thermometric bodies*, that allow the definition of empirical temperatures.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Before 1848, all temperatures were defined in this way.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] There was thus a tight link, apparently logically determined, between heat and temperature, though they were recognized as conceptually thoroughly distinct, especially by Joseph Black in the later eighteenth century.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] They break the obviously apparent link between heat and temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] They make it clear that empirical definitions of temperature are contingent on the peculiar properties of particular thermometric substances, and are thus precluded from the title 'absolute'.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] For example, water contracts on being heated near 277 K.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It cannot be used as a thermometric substance near that temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Also, over a certain temperature range, ice contracts on heating.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Moreover, many substances can exist in metastable states, such as with negative pressure, that survive only transiently and in very special conditions.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Such facts, sometimes called 'anomalous', are some of the reasons for the thermodynamic definition of absolute temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] In the early days of measurement of high temperatures, another factor was important, and used by Josiah Wedgwood in his pyrometer.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The temperature reached in a process was estimated by the shrinkage of a sample of clay.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The higher the temperature, the more the shrinkage.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] This was the only available more or less reliable method of measurement of temperatures above 1000 °C (1,832 °F).
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] The clay does not expand again on cooling.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] That is why it could be used for the measurement.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] It is not a thermometric material in the usual sense of the word.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p01] Nevertheless, the thermodynamic definition of absolute temperature does make essential use of the concept of heat, with proper circumspection.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The property of hotness is a concern of thermodynamics that should be defined without reference to the concept of heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Consideration of hotness leads to the concept of empirical temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] All physical systems are capable of heating or cooling others.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] With reference to hotness, the comparative terms hotter and colder are defined by the rule that heat flows from the hotter body to the colder.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] If a physical system is inhomogeneous or very rapidly or irregularly changing, for example by turbulence, it may be impossible to characterize it by a temperature, but still there can be transfer of energy as heat between it and another system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] If a system has a physical state that is regular enough, and persists long enough to allow it to reach thermal equilibrium with a specified thermometer, then it has a temperature according to that thermometer.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] An empirical thermometer registers degree of hotness for such a system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] For example, Truesdell writes about classical thermodynamics: "At each time, the body is assigned a real number called the *temperature*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Physical systems that are too turbulent to have temperatures may still differ in hotness.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] A physical system that passes heat to another physical system is said to be the hotter of the two.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] More is required for the system to have a thermodynamic temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Its behavior must be so regular that its empirical temperature is the same for all suitably calibrated and scaled thermometers, and then its hotness is said to lie on the one-dimensional hotness manifold.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] This is part of the reason why heat is defined following Carathéodory and Born, solely as occurring other than by work or transfer of matter; temperature is advisedly and deliberately not mentioned in this now widely accepted definition.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] This is also the reason that the zeroth law of thermodynamics is stated explicitly.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] If three physical systems, *A*, *B*, and *C* are each not in their own states of internal thermodynamic equilibrium, it is possible that, with suitable physical connections being made between them, *A* can heat *B* and *B* can heat *C* and *C* can heat *A*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] In non-equilibrium situations, cycles of flow are possible.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] That is to say, the relation 'is not colder than' between general non-equilibrium physical systems is not transitive, whereas, in contrast, the relation 'has no lower a temperature than' between thermodynamic systems in their own states of internal thermodynamic equilibrium is transitive.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] It follows from this that the relation 'is in thermal equilibrium with' is transitive, which is one way of stating the zeroth law.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Just as temperature may be undefined for a sufficiently inhomogeneous system, so also may entropy be undefined for a system not in its own state of internal thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] For example, 'the temperature of the Solar System' is not a defined quantity.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Likewise, 'the entropy of the Solar System' is not defined in classical thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] It has not been possible to define non-equilibrium entropy, as a simple number for a whole system, in a clearly satisfactory way.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The foregoing sign convention for work is used in the present article, but an alternate sign convention, followed by IUPAC, for work, is to consider the work performed on the system by its surroundings as positive.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] This is the convention adopted by many modern textbooks of physical chemistry, such as those by Peter Atkins and Ira Levine, but many textbooks on physics define work as work done by the system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The thermodynamic work done by the system is through mechanisms defined by its thermodynamic state variables, for example, its volume V, not through variables that necessarily involve mechanisms in the surroundings.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The latter are such as shaft work, and include isochoric work.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The internal energy, *U*, is a state function.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] In cyclical processes, such as the operation of a heat engine, state functions of the working substance return to their initial values upon completion of a cycle.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The differential, or infinitesimal increment, for the internal energy in an infinitesimal process is an exact differential d*U*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The symbol for exact differentials is the lowercase letter d.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] In contrast, neither of the infinitesimal increments δ*Q* nor δ*W* in an infinitesimal process represents the change in a state function of the system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Thus, infinitesimal increments of heat and work are inexact differentials.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The lowercase Greek letter delta, δ, is the symbol for inexact differentials.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The integral of any inexact differential in a process where the system leaves and then returns to the same thermodynamic state does not necessarily equal zero.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] and that *S*, the entropy of the working body, is a state function.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] with *V* the volume of the system, which is a state variable.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Associated with this differential equation is the concept that the internal energy may be considered to be a function *U* (*S*,*V*) of its natural variables *S* and *V*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The enthalpy may be considered to be a function *H*(*S*, *P*) of its natural variables *S* and *P*.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The internal energy representation and the enthalpy representation are partial Legendre transforms of one another.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] They contain the same physical information, written in different ways.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Like the internal energy, the enthalpy stated as a function of its natural variables is a thermodynamic potential and contains all thermodynamic information about a body.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] In this scenario, the increase in enthalpy is equal to the quantity of heat added to the system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] This is the basis of the determination of enthalpy changes in chemical reactions by calorimetry.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Since many processes do take place at constant atmospheric pressure, the enthalpy is sometimes given the misleading name of 'heat content' or heat function, while it actually depends strongly on the energies of covalent bonds and intermolecular forces.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] In this case, the integral specifies a quantity of heat transferred at constant pressure.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] In a transfer of energy as heat without work being done, there are changes of entropy in both the surroundings which lose heat and the system which gains it.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] It is then said that an amount of entropy Δ*S*′ has been transferred from the surroundings to the system.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] Because entropy is not a conserved quantity, this is an exception to the general way of speaking, in which an amount transferred is of a conserved quantity.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] For purposes of mathematical analysis of transfers, one thinks of fictive processes that are called *reversible*, with the temperature *T* of the system being hardly less than that of the surroundings, and the transfer taking place at an imperceptibly slow rate.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] This equality is only valid for a fictive transfer in which there is no production of entropy, that is to say, in which there is no uncompensated entropy.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] If, in contrast, the process is natural, and can really occur, with irreversibility, then there is entropy production, with d*S*uncompensated > 0.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The quantity *T* d*S*uncompensated was termed by Clausius the "uncompensated heat", though that does not accord with present-day terminology.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] $T_{surr}\,\mathrm {d} S\geq \delta Q\quad {\text{(second law)}}\,.$ which is the second law of thermodynamics for closed systems.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] In non-equilibrium thermodynamics that makes the approximation of assuming the hypothesis of local thermodynamic equilibrium, there is a special notation for this.
[src:thermodynamicist/heat-p02] The transfer of energy as heat is assumed to take place across an infinitesimal temperature difference, so that the system element and its surroundings have near enough the same temperature *T*.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In the fields of physiology and psychology, Helmholtz is known for his mathematics concerning the eye, theories of vision, ideas on the visual perception of space, colour vision research, the sensation of tone, perceptions of sound, and empiricism in the physiology of perception.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In physics, he is known for his theories on the conservation of energy and on the electrical double layer, work in electrodynamics, chemical thermodynamics, and on a mechanical foundation of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Although credit is shared with Julius von Mayer, James Joule, and Daniel Bernoulli—among others—for the energy conservation principles that eventually led to the first law of thermodynamics, he is credited with the first formulation of the energy conservation principle in its maximally general form.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] As a philosopher, he is known for his philosophy of science, ideas on the relation between the laws of perception and the laws of nature, the science of aesthetics, and ideas on the civilizing power of science.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] By the late nineteenth century, Helmholtz's development of a broadly Kantian methodology, including the *a priori* determination of the manifold of possible orientations in perceptual space, had inspired new readings of Kant and contributed to the late modern neo-Kantianism movement in philosophy.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz was born in Potsdam, the son of the local gymnasium headmaster, Ferdinand Helmholtz, who had studied classical philology and philosophy, and who was a close friend of the publisher and philosopher Immanuel Hermann Fichte.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz's work was influenced by the philosophy of Johann Gottlieb Fichte and Immanuel Kant.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He tried to trace their theories in empirical matters like physiology.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] As a young man, Helmholtz was interested in natural science, but his father wanted him to study medicine.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz earned a medical doctorate at Medizinisch-chirurgisches Friedrich-Wilhelm-Institute in 1842 and served a one-year internship at the Charité hospital (because there was financial support for medical students).
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Trained primarily in physiology, Helmholtz wrote on many other topics, ranging from theoretical physics to the age of the Earth, and to the origin of the Solar System.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz's first academic position was as a teacher of anatomy at the Academy of Arts in Berlin in 1848.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He then moved to take a post of associate professor of physiology at the Prussian University of Königsberg, where he was appointed in 1849.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In 1855 he accepted a full professorship of anatomy and physiology at the University of Bonn.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He was not particularly happy in Bonn, however, and three years later he transferred to the University of Heidelberg, in Baden, where he served as professor of physiology.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In 1871 he accepted his final university position, as professor of physics at the Friedrich Wilhelm University in Berlin.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] His first important scientific achievement, an 1847 treatise on the conservation of energy, was written in the context of his medical studies and philosophical background.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] His work on energy conservation came about while studying muscle metabolism.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He tried to demonstrate that no energy is lost in muscle movement, motivated by the implication that there were no *vital forces* necessary to move a muscle.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] This was a rejection of the speculative tradition of *Naturphilosophie* and vitalism which was at that time a dominant philosophical paradigm in German physiology.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He was working against the argument, promoted by some vitalists, that "living force" can power a machine indefinitely.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Drawing on the earlier work of Sadi Carnot, Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron and James Prescott Joule, he postulated a relationship between mechanics, heat, light, electricity and magnetism by treating them all as manifestations of a single *force*, or energy in today's terminology.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He published his theories in his book *Über die Erhaltung der Kraft* (*On the Conservation of Force*, 1847).
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In the 1850s and 60s, building on the publications of William Thomson, Helmholtz and William Rankine helped popularize the idea of the heat death of the universe.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In fluid dynamics, Helmholtz made several contributions, including Helmholtz's theorems for vortex dynamics in inviscid fluids.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz was a pioneer in the scientific study of human vision and audition.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Inspired by psychophysics, he was interested in the relationships between measurable physical stimuli and their correspondent human perceptions.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] For example, the amplitude of a sound wave can be varied, causing the sound to appear louder or softer, but a linear step in sound pressure amplitude does not result in a linear step in perceived loudness.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] The physical sound needs to be increased exponentially in order for equal steps to seem linear, a fact that is used in current electronic devices to control volume.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz paved the way in experimental studies on the relationship between the physical energy (physics) and its appreciation (psychology), with the goal in mind to develop "psychophysical laws".
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] The sensory physiology of Helmholtz was the basis of the work of Wilhelm Wundt, Helmholtz's student, who is considered one of the founders of experimental psychology.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] More explicitly than Helmholtz, Wundt described his research as a form of empirical philosophy and as a study of the mind as something separate.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz had, in his early repudiation of Naturphilosophie, stressed the importance of materialism, and was focusing more on the unity of "mind" and body.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In 1851, Helmholtz revolutionized the field of ophthalmology with the invention of the ophthalmoscope; an instrument used to examine the inside of the human eye.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz's interests at that time were increasingly focused on the physiology of the senses.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In the third and final volume, published in 1867, Helmholtz described the importance of unconscious inferences for perception.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] The *Handbuch* was first translated into English under the editorship of James P.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Southall on behalf of the Optical Society of America in 1924–5.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] His theory of accommodation went unchallenged until the final decade of the 20th century.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz continued to work for several decades on several editions of the handbook, frequently updating his work because of his dispute with Ewald Hering who held opposite views on spatial and colour vision.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] This dispute divided the discipline of physiology during the second half of the 1800s.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In 1849, while at Königsberg, Helmholtz measured the speed at which the signal is carried along a nerve fibre.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] At that time most people believed that nerve signals passed along nerves immeasurably fast.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He used a recently dissected sciatic nerve of a frog and the calf muscle to which it attached.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He used a galvanometer as a sensitive timing device, attaching a mirror to the needle to reflect a light beam across the room to a scale which gave much greater sensitivity.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz reported transmission speeds in the range of 24.6 – 38.4 meters per second.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In 1863, Helmholtz published *Sensations of Tone*, once again demonstrating his interest in the physics of perception.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] This book influenced musicologists into the twentieth century.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz invented the Helmholtz resonator to identify the various frequencies or pitches of the pure sine wave components of complex sounds containing multiple tones.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Bell failed to reproduce what he thought Helmholtz had done but later said that, had he been able to read German, he would not have gone on to invent the telephone on the harmonic telegraph principle.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Ellis was first published in 1875 (the first English edition was from the 1870 third German edition; Ellis's second English edition from the 1877 fourth German edition was published in 1885; the 1895 and 1912 third and fourth English editions were reprints of the second).
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] In 1871, Helmholtz moved from Heidelberg to Berlin to become a professor of physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] He became interested in electromagnetism, and the Helmholtz equation is named for him.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Although he made no major contributions to this field, his student Heinrich Rudolf Hertz became famous as the first to demonstrate electromagnetic radiation.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Oliver Heaviside criticised Helmholtz's electromagnetic theory because it allowed the existence of longitudinal waves.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Based on work on Maxwell's equations, Heaviside pronounced that longitudinal waves could not exist in a vacuum or a homogeneous medium.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Heaviside did not note, however, that longitudinal electromagnetic waves can exist at a boundary or in an enclosed space.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz's scientific work in physiology and mechanics occasioned much that he is known for in philosophy of science, including ideas on the relation between the laws of perception and the laws of nature and his rejection of the exclusive use of Euclidean geometry.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] His philosophy of science wavered between some version of empiricism and transcendental idealism.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Despite the speculative associations of the latter, his philosophy of science is thoroughly indebted to his use of mathematical physics to supplant vitalism and articulate the general conservation of energy principle.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] His rejection of Euclidean geometry as the only possible science of space is central to understanding his appropriation of Kant's philosophy of space, which ostensibly requires Euclidean geometry to be that exclusive *a priori* science of physical space.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Helmholtz introduced a new conception of the *a priori* in space: that of the determination of the manifold of possible orientations in perceptual space.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] These developments inspired new readings of Kant and contributed to the rise of late modern neo-Kantianism movement in philosophy.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Other students and research associates of Helmholtz at Berlin included Max Planck, Heinrich Kayser, Eugen Goldstein, Wilhelm Wien, Arthur König, Henry Augustus Rowland, Albert A.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Michelson, Wilhelm Wundt, Fernando Sanford, Arthur Gordon Webster and Michael I.
[src:thermodynamicist/hermann-von-helmholtz] Leo Koenigsberger, who was his colleague from 1869 to 1871 in Heidelberg, wrote the definitive biography of him in 1902.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Born in Belfast, he was the professor of Natural Philosophy at the University of Glasgow for 53 years.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He received the Royal Society's Copley Medal in 1883 and served as its president from 1890 to 1895.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1892 he became the first scientist to be elevated to the House of Lords.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Absolute temperatures are stated in units of kelvin in Lord Kelvin's honour.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] While the existence of a coldest possible temperature, absolute zero, was known before his work, Kelvin determined its correct value as approximately −273.15 degrees Celsius or −459.67 degrees Fahrenheit.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The Joule–Thomson effect is also named in his honour.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin worked closely with the mathematics professor Hugh Blackburn in his work.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He also had a career as an electrical telegraph engineer and inventor which propelled him into the public eye and earned him wealth, fame and honours.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] For his work on the transatlantic telegraph project, he was knighted in 1866 by Queen Victoria, becoming Sir William Thomson.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He had extensive maritime interests and worked on the mariner's compass, which previously had limited reliability.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin was ennobled in 1892 in recognition of his achievements in thermodynamics, and of his opposition to Irish Home Rule, becoming Baron Kelvin, of Largs in the County of Ayr.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The title refers to the River Kelvin, which flows near his laboratory at the University of Glasgow's Gilmorehill home at Hillhead.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Despite offers of elevated posts from several world-renowned universities, Kelvin refused to leave Glasgow, remaining until his retirement from that post in 1899.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Active in industrial research and development, he was recruited around 1899 by George Eastman to serve as vice-chairman of the board of the British company Kodak Limited, affiliated with Eastman Kodak.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1904 he became Chancellor of the University of Glasgow.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin resided in Netherhall, a mansion in Largs, which he built in the 1870s and where he died in 1907.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The Hunterian Museum at the University of Glasgow has a permanent exhibition on the work of Kelvin, which includes many of his original papers, instruments, and other artefacts, including his smoking-pipe.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] William Thomson was born on 26 June 1824 in Belfast.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His father, James Thomson, was a teacher of mathematics and engineering at the Royal Belfast Academical Institution and the son of an Ulster Scots farmer.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] James Thomson married Margaret Gardner in 1817 and, of their children, four boys and two girls survived infancy.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Margaret Thomson died in 1830 when William was six years old.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] William and his elder brother James were tutored at home by their father while the younger boys were tutored by their elder sisters.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] James was intended to benefit from the major share of his father's encouragement, affection and financial support and was prepared for a career in engineering.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1832 his father was appointed professor of mathematics at the University of Glasgow, and the family moved there in October 1833.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The Thomson children were introduced to a broader cosmopolitan experience than their father's rural upbringing, spending mid-1839 in London, and the boys were tutored in French in Paris.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Much of Thomson's life during the mid-1840s was spent in Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Language study was given a high priority.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His sister, Anna Thomson, was the mother of the physicist James Thomson Bottomley.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson attended the Royal Belfast Academical Institution, where his father was a professor of Mathematics in the university department.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1834, aged 10, he began studying at the University of Glasgow, not out of any precociousness; the university provided many of the facilities of an elementary school for able pupils, and this was a typical starting age.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In school, he showed a keen interest in the classics along with his natural interest in the sciences.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] At age 12 he won a prize for translating Lucian of Samosata's *Dialogues of the Gods* from Ancient Greek to English.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In the academic year 1839/1840, Thomson won the class prize in astronomy for his "Essay on the figure of the Earth" which showed an early facility for mathematical analysis and creativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His physics tutor at this time was David Thomson.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Throughout his life, he would work on the problems raised in the essay as a coping strategy during times of personal stress.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] On the title page of this essay Thomson wrote the following lines from Alexander Pope's "An Essay on Man".
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson became intrigued with Joseph Fourier's *Théorie analytique de la chaleur* (*The Analytical Theory of Heat*).
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He committed himself to study the "continental" mathematics resisted by a British establishment still working in the shadow of Sir Isaac Newton.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Unsurprisingly, Fourier's work had been attacked by domestic mathematicians, Philip Kelland authoring a critical book.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The book motivated Thomson to write his first published scientific paper under the pseudonym *P.Q.R.*, defending Fourier, which was submitted to *The Cambridge Mathematical Journal* by his father.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] A second P.Q.R. paper followed almost immediately.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] While on holiday with his family in Lamlash in 1841, he wrote a third, more substantial P.Q.R. paper *On the uniform motion of heat in homogeneous solid bodies, and its connection with the mathematical theory of electricity*.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] William's father was able to make a generous provision for his favourite son's education and, in 1841, installed him, with extensive letters of introduction and ample accommodation, at Peterhouse, Cambridge.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] While at Cambridge, Thomson was active in sports, athletics and sculling, winning the Colquhoun Sculls in 1843.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He took a lively interest in the classics, music, and literature; but the real love of his intellectual life was the pursuit of science.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The study of mathematics, physics, and in particular, of electricity, had captivated his imagination.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Under the tuition of William Hopkins, in 1845 Thomson graduated as second wrangler.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He also won the first Smith's Prize, which, unlike the tripos, is a test of original research.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Robert Leslie Ellis, one of the examiners, is said to have declared to another examiner "You and I are just about fit to mend his pens." He was the fourth recipient of The William Hopkins Prize (1876), awarded by the Cambridge Philosophical Society for invention or discovery.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1845 he gave the first mathematical development of Michael Faraday's idea that electric induction takes place through an intervening medium, or "dielectric", and not by some incomprehensible "action at a distance".
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He also devised the mathematical technique of electrical images, which became a powerful agent in solving problems of electrostatics, the science which deals with the forces between electrically charged bodies at rest.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] It was partly in response to his encouragement that Faraday undertook the research in September 1845 that led to the discovery of the Faraday effect, which established that light and magnetic (and thus electric) phenomena were related.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He was elected a fellow of St Peter's (as Peterhouse was often called at the time) in June 1845.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] On gaining the fellowship, he spent some time in the laboratory of the celebrated Henri Victor Regnault, at Paris; but in 1846 he was appointed to the chair of natural philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] At age 22 he found himself wearing the gown of a professor in one of the oldest universities in the country and lecturing to the class of which he was a first year student a few years before.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] By 1847 Thomson had already gained a reputation as a precocious and maverick scientist when he attended the British Association for the Advancement of Science annual meeting in Oxford.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] At that meeting, he heard James Prescott Joule making yet another of his, so far, ineffective attempts to discredit the caloric theory of heat and the theory of the heat engine built upon it by Sadi Carnot and Émile Clapeyron.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Joule argued for the mutual convertibility of heat and mechanical work and for their mechanical equivalence.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Though he felt that Joule's results demanded theoretical explanation, he retreated into an even deeper commitment to the Carnot–Clapeyron school.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He predicted that the melting point of ice must fall with pressure, otherwise its expansion on freezing could be exploited in a *perpetuum mobile*.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Experimental confirmation in his laboratory did much to bolster his beliefs.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1848, he extended the Carnot–Clapeyron theory further through his dissatisfaction that the gas thermometer provided only an operational definition of temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] "Reflections on the Motive Power of Heat", published by Carnot in French in 1824, the year of Lord Kelvin's birth, used −267 as an estimate of the absolute zero temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson used data published by Regnault to calibrate his scale against established measurements.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] —But a footnote signalled his first doubts about the caloric theory, referring to Joule's *very remarkable discoveries*.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Surprisingly, Thomson did not send Joule a copy of his paper, but when Joule eventually read it he wrote to Thomson on 6 October, claiming that his studies had demonstrated conversion of heat into work but that he was planning further experiments.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson replied on 27 October, revealing that he was planning his own experiments and hoping for a reconciliation of their two sides.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson returned to critique Carnot's original publication and read his analysis to the Royal Society of Edinburgh in January 1849, still convinced that the theory was fundamentally sound.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] However, though Thomson conducted no new experiments, over the next two years he became increasingly dissatisfied with Carnot's theory and convinced of Joule's.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In February 1851 he sat down to articulate his new thinking.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He was uncertain of how to frame his theory, and the paper went through several drafts before he settled on an attempt to reconcile Carnot and Joule.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] During his rewriting, he seems to have considered ideas that would subsequently give rise to the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In Carnot's theory, lost heat was *absolutely lost,* but Thomson contended that it was "*lost to man* irrecoverably; but not lost in the material world".
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Moreover, his theological beliefs led Thomson to extrapolate the second law to the cosmos, originating the idea of universal heat death.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson also formulated the heat death paradox (Kelvin's paradox) in 1862, which uses the second law of thermodynamics to disprove the possibility of an infinitely old universe; this paradox was later extended by William Rankine.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] As soon as Joule read the paper he wrote to Thomson with his comments and questions.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thus began a fruitful, though largely epistolary, collaboration between the two men, Joule conducting experiments, Thomson analysing the results and suggesting further experiments.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The collaboration lasted from 1852 to 1856, its discoveries including the Joule–Thomson effect, sometimes called the Kelvin–Joule effect, and the published results did much to bring about general acceptance of Joule's work and the kinetic theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson published more than 650 scientific papers and applied for 70 patents (not all were issued).
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Though eminent in the academic field, Thomson was obscure to the general public.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In September 1852, he married childhood sweetheart Margaret Crum, daughter of Walter Crum; but her health broke down on their honeymoon, and over the next 17 years Thomson was distracted by her suffering.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] On 16 October 1854 George Gabriel Stokes wrote to Thomson to try to re-interest him in work by asking his opinion on some experiments of Faraday on the proposed transatlantic telegraph cable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Faraday had demonstrated how the construction of a cable would limit the rate at which messages could be sent - in modern terms, the bandwidth.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson jumped at the problem and published his response that month.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He expressed his results in terms of the data rate that could be achieved and the economic consequences in terms of the potential revenue of the transatlantic undertaking.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In a further 1855 analysis, Thomson stressed the impact that the design of the cable would have on its profitability.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson contended that the signalling speed through a given cable was inversely proportional to the square of the length of the cable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's results were disputed at a meeting of the British Association in 1856 by Wildman Whitehouse, the electrician of the Atlantic Telegraph Company.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Whitehouse had possibly misinterpreted the results of his own experiments but was doubtless feeling financial pressure as plans for the cable were already well under way.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He believed that Thomson's calculations implied that the cable must be "abandoned as being practically and commercially impossible".
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson attacked Whitehouse's contention in a letter to the popular *Athenaeum* magazine, pitching himself into the public eye.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson recommended a larger conductor with a larger cross section of insulation.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He thought Whitehouse no fool and suspected that he might have the practical skill to make the existing design work.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's work had attracted the attention of the project's undertakers.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In December 1856, he was elected to the board of directors of the Atlantic Telegraph Company.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson became scientific adviser to a team with Whitehouse as chief electrician and Sir Charles Tilston Bright as chief engineer, but Whitehouse had his way with the specification, supported by Faraday and Samuel Morse.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson sailed on board the cable-laying ship HMS *Agamemnon* in August 1857, with Whitehouse confined to land owing to illness, but the voyage ended after 380 miles (610 km) when the cable parted.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson developed a complete system for operating a submarine telegraph that was capable of sending a character every 3.5 seconds.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He patented the key elements of his system, the mirror galvanometer and the siphon recorder, in 1858.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Whitehouse still felt able to ignore Thomson's many suggestions and proposals.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] It was not until Thomson convinced the board that using purer copper for replacing the lost section of cable would improve data capacity, that he first made a difference to the execution of the project.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The board insisted that Thomson join the 1858 cable-laying expedition, without any financial compensation, and take an active part in the project.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In return, Thomson secured a trial for his mirror galvanometer, which the board had been unenthusiastic about, alongside Whitehouse's equipment.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson found the access he was given unsatisfactory, and the *Agamemnon* had to return home following a disastrous storm in June 1858.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In London, the board was about to abandon the project and mitigate their losses by selling the cable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Field and Curtis Lampson argued for another attempt and prevailed, Thomson insisting that the technical problems were tractable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Though employed in an advisory capacity, Thomson had, during the voyages, developed a real engineer's instincts and skill at practical problem-solving under pressure, often taking the lead in dealing with emergencies and being unafraid to assist in manual work.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's fears were realised when Whitehouse's apparatus proved insufficiently sensitive and had to be replaced by Thomson's mirror galvanometer.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Whitehouse continued to maintain that it was his equipment that was providing the service and started to engage in desperate measures to remedy some of the problems.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He fatally damaged the cable by applying a "jolt" of high voltage electricity from 5-foot (1.5 m)-long induction coils on shore at Valentia Island, the eastern landfall of the cable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] When the cable failed completely Whitehouse was dismissed, though Thomson objected and was reprimanded by the board for his interference.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson subsequently regretted that he had acquiesced too readily to many of Whitehouse's proposals and had not challenged him with sufficient vigour.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] A joint committee of inquiry was established by the Board of Trade and the Atlantic Telegraph Company.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Most of the blame for the cable's failure was found to rest with Whitehouse.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The committee found that, though underwater cables were notorious in their lack of reliability, most of the problems arose from known and avoidable causes.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson was appointed one of a five-member committee to recommend a specification for a new cable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In July 1865, Thomson sailed on the cable-laying expedition of the SS *Great Eastern*, but the voyage was dogged by technical problems.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The cable was lost after 1,200 miles (1,900 km) had been laid, and the project was abandoned.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] A further attempt in 1866 laid a new cable in two weeks, and then recovered and completed the 1865 cable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The enterprise was feted as a triumph by the public, and Thomson enjoyed a large share of the adulation.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson, along with the other principals of the project, was knighted on 10 November 1866.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] To exploit his inventions for signalling on long submarine cables, Thomson entered into a partnership with C.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In conjunction with the latter, he also devised an automatic curb sender, a kind of telegraph key for sending messages on a cable.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson took part in the laying of the French Atlantic submarine communications cable of 1869, and with Jenkin was engineer of the Western and Brazilian and Platino-Brazilian cables, assisted by the vacation student Alfred Ewing.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He was present at the laying of the Pará to Pernambuco section of the Brazilian coast cables in 1873.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's wife, Margaret, died on 17 June 1870, and he resolved to make changes in his life.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Already addicted to seafaring, in September he purchased a 126-ton schooner, the *Lalla Rookh* and used it as a base for entertaining friends and scientific colleagues.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His maritime interests continued in 1871 when he was appointed to the Board of Enquiry into the sinking of HMS *Captain*.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In June 1873 Thomson and Jenkin were on board the *Hooper*, bound for Lisbon with 2,500 miles (4,020 km) of cable when the cable developed a fault.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] An unscheduled 16-day stop-over in Madeira followed, and Thomson became good friends with Charles R.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] On 2 May 1874 he set sail for Madeira on the *Lalla Rookh*.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] As he approached the harbour, he signalled to the Blandy residence "Will you marry me?" and Fanny (Blandy's daughter Frances Anna Blandy) signalled back "Yes".
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson married Fanny, 13 years his junior, on 24 June 1874.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Over the period 1855 to 1867, Thomson collaborated with Peter Guthrie Tait on a textbook that founded the study of mechanics first on the mathematics of kinematics, the description of motion without regard to force.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The text developed dynamics in various areas but with constant attention to energy as a unifying principle.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] A second edition appeared in 1879, expanded to two separately bound parts.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The textbook set a standard for early education in mathematical physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson made significant contributions to atmospheric electricity for the relatively short time for which he worked on the subject, around 1859.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He developed several instruments for measuring the atmospheric electric field, using some of the electrometers he had initially developed for telegraph work, which he tested at Glasgow and whilst on holiday on Arran.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His measurements on Arran were sufficiently rigorous and well-calibrated that they could be used to deduce air pollution from the Glasgow area, through its effects on the atmospheric electric field.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's water dropper electrometer was used for measuring the atmospheric electric field at Kew Observatory and Eskdalemuir Observatory for many years, and one was still in use operationally at the Kakioka Observatory in Japan until early 2021.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson may have unwittingly observed atmospheric electrical effects caused by the Carrington Event (a significant geomagnetic storm) in early September 1859.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Between 1870 and 1890 the vortex atom theory, which purported that an atom was a vortex in the aether, was popular among British physicists and mathematicians.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] About 60 scientific papers were written by approximately 25 scientists.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Following the lead of Thomson and Tait, the branch of topology called knot theory was developed.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's initiative in this complex study that continues to inspire new mathematics has led to persistence of the topic in history of science.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson was an enthusiastic yachtsman, his interest in all things relating to the sea perhaps arising from, or fostered by, his experiences on the *Agamemnon* and the *Great Eastern*.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson introduced a new method of deep-sea depth sounding, in which a steel piano wire replaces the ordinary hand line.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The wire glides so easily to the bottom that "flying soundings" can be taken while the ship is at full speed.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson added a pressure gauge to register the depth of the sinker.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] About the same time he revived the Sumner method of finding a ship's position, and calculated a set of tables for its ready application.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] During the 1880s, Thomson worked to perfect the adjustable compass to correct errors arising from magnetic deviation owing to the increased use of iron in naval architecture.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's design was a great improvement on the older instruments, being steadier and less hampered by friction.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The deviation caused by the ship's magnetism was corrected by movable iron masses at the binnacle.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's innovations involved much detailed work to develop principles identified by George Biddell Airy and others, but contributed little in terms of novel physical thinking.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's energetic lobbying and networking proved effective in gaining acceptance of his instrument by The Admiralty.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson did more than any other electrician up to his time in introducing accurate methods and devices for measuring electricity.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] As early as 1845 he pointed out that the experimental results of William Snow Harris were in accordance with the laws of Charles-Augustin de Coulomb.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In the *Memoirs of the Roman Academy of Sciences* for 1857 he published a description of his divided ring electrometer, based on the electroscope of Johann Gottlieb Friedrich von Bohnenberger.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He introduced a chain or series of effective instruments, including the quadrant electrometer, which cover the entire field of electrostatic measurement.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He invented the current balance, also known as the *Kelvin balance* or *Ampere balance* (*SiC*), for the precise specification of the ampere, the standard unit of electric current.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] From around 1880 he was aided by the electrical engineer Magnus Maclean FRSE in his electrical experiments.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1893, Thomson headed an international commission to decide on the design of the Niagara Falls power station.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Despite his belief in the superiority of direct current electric power transmission, he endorsed Westinghouse's alternating current system which had been demonstrated at the Chicago World's Fair of that year.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Even after Niagara Falls, Thomson still held to his belief that direct current was the superior system.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Acknowledging his contribution to electrical standardisation, the International Electrotechnical Commission elected Thomson as its first president at its preliminary meeting, held in London on 26–27 June 1906.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] "On the proposal of the President [Mr Alexander Siemens, Great Britain], secounded [sic] by Mr Mailloux [US Institute of Electrical Engineers] the Right Honorable Lord Kelvin, G.C.V.O., O.M., was unanimously elected first President of the Commission", minutes of the Preliminary Meeting Report read.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin made an early physics-based estimation of the age of Earth.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Given his youthful work on the figure of Earth and his interest in heat conduction, it is no surprise that he chose to investigate Earth's cooling and to make historical inferences of Earth's age from his calculations.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He developed the view that Earth had once been too hot to support life and contrasted this view with that of uniformitarianism, that conditions had remained constant since the indefinite past.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] After the publication of Charles Darwin's *On the Origin of Species* in 1859, Thomson saw evidence of the relatively short habitable age of Earth as tending to contradict Darwin's gradualist explanation of slow natural selection bringing about biological diversity.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's own views favoured a version of theistic evolution sped up by divine guidance.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He proposed that life on Earth had evolved from plants, the seeds of which had been carried from other planets by meteorites.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His calculations showed that the Sun could not have possibly existed long enough to allow the slow incremental development by evolution—unless it was heated by an energy source beyond the knowledge of Victorian era science.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He was soon drawn into public disagreement with geologists and with Darwin's supporters John Tyndall and Thomas Henry Huxley.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In his response to Huxley's address to the Geological Society of London (1868) he presented his address "Of Geological Dynamics" (1869) which, among his other writings, challenged the geologists' assertion that Earth must be vastly old, perhaps billions of years in age.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson's initial 1864 estimate of Earth's age was from 20 to 400 million years old.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] These wide limits were due to his uncertainty about the melting temperature of rock, to which he equated Earth's interior temperature, as well as the uncertainty in thermal conductivities and specific heats of rocks.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Over the years he refined his arguments and reduced the upper bound by a factor of ten, and in 1897 Thomson, now Lord Kelvin, ultimately settled on an estimate that Earth was 20–40 million years old.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In a letter published in Scientific American Supplement 1895 Kelvin criticised geologists' estimates of the age of rocks and the age of Earth, including the views published by Darwin, as "vaguely vast age".
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His exploration of this estimate can be found in his 1897 address to the Victoria Institute, given at the request of the institute's president George Stokes, as recorded in that institute's journal *Transactions*.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Although his former assistant John Perry published a paper in 1895 challenging Kelvin's assumption of low thermal conductivity inside Earth, and thus showing a much greater age, this had little immediate impact.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The discovery of radioactivity largely invalidated Kelvin's estimate of the age of Earth.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Although he eventually paid off a gentleman's bet with Strutt on the importance of radioactivity in Earth's geology, he never publicly acknowledged this because he thought he had a much stronger argument restricting the age of the Sun to no more than 20 million years.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Without sunlight, there could be no explanation for the sediment record on Earth's surface.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] At the time, the only known source for solar energy was gravitational collapse.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] It was only when thermonuclear fusion was recognised in the 1930s that Kelvin's age paradox was truly resolved.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] However, modern cosmology recognises the Kelvin period in the early life of a star, during which it shines from gravitational energy (correctly calculated by Kelvin) before fusion and the main sequence begins.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The question of how to manipulate a set of differential equations into a form suitable for analogue computation was posed, and partially answered by Lord Kelvin.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He proposed implementation using a mechanical integrator designed by his brother, James Thomson, but practical difficulties prevented implementation in his lifetime.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His approach underlies the conversion of a set of differential equations to a state-space form suitable for digital computation.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In the winter of 1860–61, Kelvin (aged 37) slipped on the ice while curling near his home at Netherhall and fractured his leg, causing him to miss the 1861 Manchester meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science and to limp thereafter.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He remained something of a celebrity on both sides of the Atlantic until his death.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thomson remained a devout believer in Christianity throughout his life; attendance at chapel was part of his daily routine.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He saw his Christian faith as supporting and informing his scientific work, as is evident from his address to the annual meeting of the Christian Evidence Society on 23 May 1889.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In the 1902 Coronation Honours list published on 26 June 1902 (the original day of the coronation of Edward VII and Alexandra), Kelvin was appointed a Privy Councillor and one of the first members of the new Order of Merit (OM).
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He received the order from the King on 8 August 1902 and was sworn a member of the council at Buckingham Palace on 11 August 1902.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In his later years he often travelled to his townhouse at 15 Eaton Place, off Eaton Square in Belgravia, London.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In November 1907 he caught a chill and his condition deteriorated until he died at his Scottish country seat, Netherhall, in Largs on 17 December.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] At the request of Westminster Abbey, the undertakers Wylie & Lochhead prepared an oak coffin lined with lead.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In the dark of the winter evening the cortege set off from Netherhall for Largs railway station, a distance of about a mile.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Large crowds witnessed the passing of the cortege, and shopkeepers closed their premises and dimmed their lights.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The coffin was placed in a special Midland and Glasgow and South Western Railway van.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The train set off at 8:30 pm for Kilmarnock, where the van was attached to the overnight express to St Pancras railway station in London.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin's funeral was on 23 December 1907.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The Abbey was crowded, including representatives from the University of Glasgow and the University of Cambridge, along with representatives from France, Italy, Germany, Austria-Hungary, Russia, the United States, Canada, Australia, Japan and Monaco.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin's grave is in the nave, near the choir screen, and close to the graves of Isaac Newton, John Herschel, and Charles Darwin.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Darwin's son, Sir George Darwin, was one of the pall-bearers.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The University of Glasgow held a memorial service for Kelvin in the Bute Hall.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin had been a member of the Scottish Episcopal Church, attached to St Columba's Episcopal Church in Largs, and when in Glasgow to St Mary's Episcopal Church (now, St Mary's Cathedral, Glasgow).
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] At the same time as the funeral in Westminster Abbey, a service was held in St Columba's Episcopal Church, Largs, attended by a large congregation including burgh dignitaries.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Lord Kelvin is memorialised on the Thomson family grave in Glasgow Necropolis.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The family grave has a second modern memorial, erected by the Royal Philosophical Society of Glasgow, a society of which he was president in the periods 1856–58 and 1874–77.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1884 Kelvin led a master class on "Molecular Dynamics and the Wave Theory of Light" at Johns Hopkins University.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin referred to the acoustic wave equation describing sound as waves of pressure in air and attempted to describe also an electromagnetic wave equation, presuming a luminiferous aether susceptible to vibration.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Morley who subsequently performed the Michelson–Morley experiment, which found no luminiferous aether.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Hathaway took notes and duplicated them with a papyrograph.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] As the subject matter was under active development, Kelvin amended that text and in 1904 it was typeset and published.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Kelvin's attempts to provide mechanical models ultimately failed in the electromagnetic regime.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Starting from his lecture in 1884, he was the first scientist to formulate the hypothetical concept of dark matter; he then attempted to define and locate some "dark bodies" in the Milky Way.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] He was sceptical about Maxwell's prediction of radiation pressure, but admitted that it did exist after seeing Pyotr Lebedev's experimental proof of radiation pressure.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] On 27 April 1900 he gave a widely reported lecture titled "Nineteenth-Century Clouds over the Dynamical Theory of Heat and Light" to the Royal Institution.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The two "dark clouds" he was alluding to were confusion surrounding how matter moves through the aether (including the puzzling results of the Michelson–Morley experiment) and indications that the equipartition theorem in statistical mechanics might break down.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Two major physical theories were developed during the 20th century starting from these issues: for the former, the theory of relativity; for the second, quantum mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Like many scientists, Thomson made some mistakes in predicting the future of technology.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Thompson, writes that, "When Röntgen's discovery of the X-rays was announced at the end of 1895, Lord Kelvin was entirely sceptical, and regarded the announcement as a hoax.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The papers had been full of the wonders of Röntgen's rays, about which Lord Kelvin was intensely sceptical until Röntgen himself sent him a copy of his Memoir".
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] On 17 January 1896, having read the paper and seen the photographs, he wrote Röntgen a letter saying that, "I need not tell you that when I read the paper I was very much astonished and delighted.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] I can say no more now than to congratulate you warmly on the great discovery you have made." Kelvin had his own hand X-rayed in May 1896.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] His forecast for practical aviation (i.e., heavier-than-air aircraft) was negative.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] A statement falsely attributed to Kelvin is: "There is nothing new to be discovered in physics now.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] All that remains is more and more precise measurement." This has been widely misattributed to Kelvin since the 1980s, either without citation or stating that it was made in an address to the British Association for the Advancement of Science (1900).
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] There is no evidence that Kelvin said this, and the quote is instead a paraphrase of Albert A.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Michelson, who in 1894 stated: "... it seems probable that most of the grand underlying principles have been firmly established ...
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] An eminent physicist remarked that the future truths of physical science are to be looked for in the sixth place of decimals." Similar statements were given earlier by others, such as Philipp von Jolly.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] The attribution to Kelvin in 1900 is presumably a confusion with his "Two clouds" lecture and which on the contrary pointed out areas that would subsequently see revolutions.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] In 1898 Kelvin predicted that only 400 years of oxygen supply remained on the planet, due to the rate of burning combustibles.
[src:thermodynamicist/lord-kelvin] Mount Kelvin in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him by botanist William Trownson.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck made many contributions to theoretical physics, primarily in his role as the originator of quantum theory and one of the founders of modern physics, which revolutionized understanding of atomic and subatomic processes.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He is known for the Planck constant, h , which is of foundational importance for quantum physics, and which he used to derive a set of units, now called Planck units, expressed in terms of physical constants.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The Planck relation, E= h ν, states that the energy of a photon is proportional to its frequency.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was twice President of the Kaiser Wilhelm Society.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1948 it was renamed the Max Planck Society, and today includes 83 institutions representing a wide range of scientific disciplines.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Max Karl Ernst Ludwig Planck was born on 23 April 1858 in Kiel, the son of Johann Julius Wilhelm Planck and his second wife, Emma Patzig.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He was baptized with the name of *Karl Ernst Ludwig Marx Planck*; of his given names, *Marx* was indicated as the "appellation name".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] However, by the age of ten he signed with the name *Max* and used this for the rest of his life.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck came from a traditional, intellectual family.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] His paternal great-grandfather and grandfather were both theology professors at the University of Göttingen; his father was a law professor at Kiel University and the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was the sixth child in the family, though two of his siblings were from his father's first marriage.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] War was common during Planck's early years and among his earliest memories was the marching of Prussian and Austrian troops into Kiel during the Second Schleswig War in 1864.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1867, the family moved to Munich, where Planck enrolled at Maximiliansgymnasium.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] There, his mathematical talents emerged early and he later came under the tutelage of Hermann Müller, a mathematician who took an interest in the youth, and taught him astronomy and mechanics as well as mathematics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] It was from Müller that Planck first learned the law of conservation of energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] This is how Planck first came in contact with the field of physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was gifted in music; he took singing lessons and played piano, organ and cello, and composed songs and operas.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1874, Planck enrolled at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Under professor Philipp von Jolly's supervision, Planck performed the only experiments of his scientific career, studying the diffusion of hydrogen through heated platinum, but then transferred to theoretical physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1877, Planck went to the Friedrich Wilhelm University of Berlin for a year of study with physicists Hermann von Helmholtz and Gustav Kirchhoff and mathematician Karl Weierstrass.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He wrote that Helmholtz was never quite prepared, spoke slowly, miscalculated endlessly, and bored his listeners, while Kirchhoff spoke in carefully prepared lectures which were dry and monotonous.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He soon became a close friend with Helmholtz.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] While there he undertook a program of mostly self-study of Rudolf Clausius' writings, which led him to choose thermodynamics as his field.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In October 1878, Planck passed his qualifying exams and in February 1879 defended his thesis *Über den zweiten Hauptsatz der mechanischen Wärmetheorie* (*On the second law of mechanical heat theory*).
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He briefly taught mathematics and physics at his former school in Munich.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] By the year 1880, Planck had obtained the two highest academic degrees offered in Europe.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The first was a doctorate degree after he completed his paper detailing his research and theory of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He then presented his habilitation thesis entitled *Gleichgewichtszustände isotroper Körper in verschiedenen Temperaturen* (*Equilibrium states of isotropic bodies at different temperatures*).
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1880, Planck became a *Privatdozent* (unsalaried lecturer) at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München, waiting until he was offered an academic position.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Although he was initially ignored by the academic community, he furthered his work on the field of heat theory and discovered one after another the same thermodynamical formalism as Gibbs without realizing it.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Clausius' ideas on entropy occupied a central role in his work.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In April 1885, Planck was appointed associate professor of Theoretical Physics at Kiel University.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Further work on entropy and its treatment, especially as applied in physical chemistry, followed.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He published his *Treatise on Thermodynamics* in 1897.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He proposed a thermodynamic basis for Svante Arrhenius's theory of electrolytic dissociation.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1889, Planck was named the successor to Kirchhoff's position at the Friedrich Wilhelm University of Berlin – presumably thanks to Helmholtz's intercession – and by 1892 became Full Professor.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1907, he was offered Ludwig Boltzmann's position in Vienna, but turned it down to stay in Berlin.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] During 1909, as a professor at the Friedrich Wilhelm University of Berlin, he was invited to become the Ernest Kempton Adams Lecturer in Theoretical Physics at Columbia University in New York City.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] A series of his lectures were translated and co-published by Columbia University professor A.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He retired from Berlin on 10 January 1926, and was succeeded by Erwin Schrödinger.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] As a professor at the Friedrich Wilhelm University of Berlin, Planck joined the local Physical Society.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He later wrote about this time: "In those days I was essentially the only theoretical physicist there, whence things were not so easy for me, because I started mentioning entropy, but this was not quite fashionable, since it was regarded as a mathematical spook".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Thanks to his initiative, the various local Physical Societies of Germany merged in 1898 to form the German Physical Society (Deutsche Physikalische Gesellschaft, DPG); from 1905 to 1909 Planck was the president.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck started a six-semester course of lectures on theoretical physics, "dry, somewhat impersonal" according to Lise Meitner, "using no notes, never making mistakes, never faltering; the best lecturer I ever heard" according to an English participant, James R.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Partington, who continues: "There were always many standing around the room.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Thermodynamics, also known as the "mechanical theory of heat" at the end of the 19th century, had emerged at the beginning of this century from an attempt to understand the functioning of steam engines and to improve their efficiency.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In the 1840s, several researchers independently discovered and formulated the law of conservation of energy, which is now also known as the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1850, Rudolf Clausius formulated the so-called second law of thermodynamics, which states that a voluntary (or spontaneous) transfer of energy is only possible from a warmer to a colder body, but not vice versa.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In England at this time William Thomson came to the same conclusion.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Clausius generalized his formulation further and further and came up with a new formulation in 1865.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] To this end, he introduced the concept of entropy, which he defined as a measure of the reversible supply of heat in relation to the absolute temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The new formulation of the second law, which is still valid today, was: "Entropy can be created, but never destroyed".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Clausius, whose work Planck read as a young student during his stay in Berlin, successfully applied this new law of nature to mechanical, thermoelectric and chemical processes.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In his thesis in 1879, Planck summarized Clausius' writings, pointing out contradictions and inaccuracies in their formulation and then clarifying them.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In addition, he generalized the validity of the second law to all processes in nature; Clausius had limited its application to reversible processes and thermal processes.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In reversible processes, the entropy remains constant.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He presented this fact in detail in 1887 in a series of treatises entitled "On the Principle of the Increase of Entropy".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In his study of the concept of entropy, Planck did not follow the molecular, probabilistic interpretation that prevailed at the time, as these do not provide absolute proof of universality.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Instead, he pursued a phenomenological approach and was also skeptical of atomism.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Even though he later abandoned this attitude in the course of his work on the law of radiation, his early work impressively shows the possibilities of thermodynamics in solving concrete physicochemical problems.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck's understanding of entropy included the realization that the maximum of entropy corresponds to the equilibrium state.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The accompanying conclusion that knowledge of the Entropy allows all laws of thermodynamic equilibrium states to be derived corresponds to the modern understanding of such states.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck therefore chose equilibrium processes as his research focus and, based on his habilitation thesis, researched the coexistence of aggregate states and the equilibrium of gas reactions, for example.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] This work on the frontier of chemical thermodynamics also received great attention due to the rapidly expanding chemical work at that time.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Independently of Planck, Josiah Willard Gibbs had also discovered almost all the knowledge Planck gained about the properties of physicochemical equilibria and published them from 1876 onwards.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was unaware of these essays, and they did not appear in German until 1892.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] However, both scientists approached the topic in different ways, while Planck dealt with irreversible processes, Gibbs looked at equilibria.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] This approach was finally able to prevail because of its simplicity, but Planck's approach is attributed the greater universality.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In addition to his research on entropy, Planck dedicated the first decade of his scientific career to the study of electrical processes in solutions.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] During this period, he succeeded in theoretically deriving the relationship between the conductivity and dilution of a solution, thereby establishing the foundations of modern electrolyte theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He was also able to provide a theoretical derivation for the conditions governing the changes in freezing and boiling points of dilute solutions, phenomena which had been empirically discovered by François-Marie Raoult and Jacobus Henricus van ’t Hoff in 1886.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1894, Planck turned his attention to the problem of black-body radiation.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The problem had been stated by Kirchhoff in 1859: "how does the intensity of the electromagnetic radiation emitted by a black body (a perfect absorber, also known as a cavity radiator) depend on the frequency of the radiation (i.e., the color of the light) and the temperature of the body?".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The question had been explored experimentally, but no theoretical treatment had agreed with the experimentally observed evidence.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Wilhelm Wien proposed Wien's law, which correctly predicted the behaviour at high frequencies, but failed at low frequencies.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The Rayleigh–Jeans law, another approach to the problem, agreed with experimental results at low frequencies, but created what was later known as the "ultraviolet catastrophe" at high frequencies, as predicted by classical physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] However, contrary to many textbooks, this was not a motivation for Planck.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck's first proposed solution to the problem in 1899 followed from what he called the "principle of elementary disorder", which allowed him to derive Wien's law from a number of assumptions about the entropy of an ideal oscillator, creating what was referred to as the Wien–Planck law.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Soon, however, it was found that experimental evidence did not confirm the new law at all, to Planck's frustration.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He revised his approach and now derived the first version of the famous Planck black-body radiation law, which described clearly the experimentally observed black-body spectrum.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] It was first proposed in a meeting of the DPG on 19 October 1900 and published in 1901.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was deeply suspicious of the philosophical and physical implications of such an interpretation of Boltzmann's approach; thus his recourse to them was, as he later put it, "an act of despair ...
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] I was ready to sacrifice any of my previous convictions about physics".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] where *h* is the Planck constant, also known as Planck's action quantum (introduced already in 1899), and *ν* is the frequency of the radiation.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Note that the elementary units of energy discussed here are represented by *hν* and not simply by *ν*.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Physicists now call these quanta photons, and a photon of frequency *ν* will have its own specific and unique energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The total energy at that frequency is then equal to *hν* multiplied by the number of photons at that frequency.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He explained: "Radiant heat is not a continuous flow and indefinitely divisible. ...
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] (Boltzmann had been discussing in a theoretical paper in 1877 the possibility that the energy states of a physical system could be discrete).
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The discovery of the Planck constant enabled him to define a new universal set of physical units (such as the Planck length and the Planck mass), all based on fundamental physical constants, upon which much of quantum theory is based.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In a discussion with his son in December 1918 Planck described his discovery as 'a discovery of the first rank, comparable perhaps only to the discoveries of Newton'.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In recognition of Planck's fundamental contribution to a new branch of physics, he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for 1918; (he received the award in 1919).
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Subsequently, Planck tried to grasp the meaning of energy quanta, but to no avail.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] "I am unable to understand Jeans' stubbornness – he is an example of a theoretician as should never be existing, the same as Hegel was for philosophy.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Max Born wrote about Planck: "He was, by nature, a conservative mind; he had nothing of the revolutionary and was thoroughly skeptical about speculations.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1905, Albert Einstein published three papers in the journal *Annalen der Physik*.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was among the few who immediately recognized the significance of the special theory of relativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Thanks to his influence, this theory was soon widely accepted in Germany.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck also contributed considerably to extend the special theory of relativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] For example, he recast the theory in terms of classical action.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Einstein's hypothesis of light *quanta* (photons), based on Heinrich Hertz's 1887 discovery (and further investigation by Philipp Lenard) of the photoelectric effect, was initially rejected by Planck.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He was unwilling to discard completely Maxwell's theory of electrodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1910, Einstein pointed out the anomalous behavior of specific heat at low temperatures as another example of a phenomenon which defies explanation by classical physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck and Walther Nernst, seeking to clarify the increasing number of contradictions, organized the First Solvay Conference (Brussels 1911).
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] At this meeting Einstein was able to convince Planck.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Meanwhile, Planck had been appointed dean of the Friedrich Wilhelm University of Berlin, whereby it was possible for him to appoint Einstein to Berlin and establish a new professorship for him (1914).
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Soon, the two scientists became close friends and met frequently to play music together.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1915, when Italy was still a neutral power, Planck voted successfully for a scientific paper from Italy, which received a prize from the Prussian Academy of Sciences, where Planck was one of four permanent presidents.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In the turbulent post-war years, Planck, now the highest authority of German physics, issued the slogan "persevere and continue working" to his colleagues.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In October 1920, he and Fritz Haber established the Notgemeinschaft der Deutschen Wissenschaft, aimed at providing financial support for scientific research.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] A considerable portion of the money the organization would distribute was raised abroad.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck held leading positions at the Friedrich Wilhelm University of Berlin, the Prussian Academy of Sciences, the German Physical Society, and the Kaiser Wilhelm Society (which became the Max Planck Society in 1948).
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] During this time economic conditions in Germany were such that he was hardly able to conduct research.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] During the interwar period, Planck became a member of the German People's Party, the party of Nobel Peace Prize laureate Gustav Stresemann, which aspired to liberal aims for domestic policy and rather revisionistic aims for politics around the world.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] At the end of the 1920s, Niels Bohr, Werner Heisenberg, and Wolfgang Pauli had worked out the Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics, but it was rejected by Planck, and by Schrödinger, Laue, and Einstein as well.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck expected that wave mechanics would soon render quantum theory – his own child – unnecessary.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Further work only served to underscore the enduring central importance of quantum theory, even against his and Einstein's philosophical revulsions.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] It took only 10 years for 75% of British scientists to generally accept Charles Darwin's ideas from *On the Origin of Species* and science historian I.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Bernard Cohen noted that, to the contrary, Planck's own ideas were generally accepted by his peers.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Plate tectonics also took only a decade to be adopted by geologists evidenced by its use in textbooks.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Brad Wray's research into the history of scientific ideas showed that older scientists are only marginally less inclined to accept new conceptualizations.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] When the Nazis came to power in 1933, Planck was 74 years old.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He witnessed many Jewish friends and colleagues expelled from their positions and humiliated, and hundreds of scientists emigrate from Nazi Germany.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He again tried to "persevere and continue working" and asked scientists who were considering emigration to remain in Germany.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Nevertheless, he helped his nephew, the economist Hermann Kranold, to emigrate to London after his arrest.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He hoped the crisis would abate soon and the political situation would improve.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was therefore unsuccessful, since this reply "took from him every basis for further negotiation", as to Hitler "the Jews are all Communists, and these are [his] enemies." In the following year, 1934, Haber died in exile.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] One year later, Planck, having been the president of the KWG since 1930, organized in a somewhat provocative style an official commemorative meeting for Haber.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He also succeeded in secretly enabling a number of Jewish scientists to continue working in institutes of the KWG for several years.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1936, his term as president of the KWG ended, and the Nazi government pressured him to refrain from seeking another term.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The "Hauptamt Wissenschaft" (Nazi government office for science) started an investigation of Planck's ancestry, claiming that he was "1/16 Jewish", but Planck denied it.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1938, Planck celebrated his 80th birthday.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The DPG held a celebration, during which the Max-Planck medal (founded as the highest medal by the DPG in 1928) was awarded to French physicist Louis de Broglie.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] At the end of 1938, the Prussian Academy lost its remaining independence and was taken over by Nazis, as part of their process of *Gleichschaltung*.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck protested by resigning his presidency.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He continued to travel frequently, giving numerous public talks, such as his talk on Religion and Science and, five years later, he was sufficiently fit to climb 3,000-metre peaks in the Alps.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] During the Second World War, the increasing number of Allied bombing missions against Berlin forced Planck and his wife to temporarily leave the city and live in the countryside.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] His rural retreat was threatened by the rapid advance of the Allied armies from both sides.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In 1944, Planck's son Erwin was arrested by the Gestapo following the attempted assassination of Hitler in the 20 July plot.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He was tried and sentenced to death by the People's Court in October 1944.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Erwin was hanged at Berlin's Plötzensee Prison in January 1945.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The death of his son destroyed much of Planck's will to live.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In March 1887, Planck married Marie Merck (1861–1909), sister of a school fellow, and moved with her into a sublet apartment in Kiel.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] After living in the apartment in Berlin, the Planck family lived in a villa in Berlin-Grunewald, Wangenheimstrasse 21.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Several other professors of the Friedrich Wilhelm University of Berlin lived nearby, among them theologian Adolf von Harnack, who became a close friend of Planck.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Soon the Planck home became a social and cultural center.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Numerous well-known scientists, such as Albert Einstein, Otto Hahn and Lise Meitner were frequent visitors.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] The tradition of jointly performing music had already been established in the home of Helmholtz.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] After several happy years, in July 1909 Marie Planck died, possibly of tuberculosis.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In March 1911 Planck married his second wife, Marga von Hoesslin (1882–1948); in December his fifth child, Hermann, was born.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] During the First World War, Planck's second son, Erwin, was taken prisoner by the French in 1914, while his oldest son, Karl, was killed in action at Verdun.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Grete died in 1917 while giving birth to her first child.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Her sister died the same way two years later, after having married Grete's widower.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Both granddaughters survived and were named after their mothers.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] In January 1945, Erwin Planck, to whom he had been particularly close, was sentenced to death by the People's Court because of his participation in the failed attempt to assassinate Hitler in July 1944.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] After World War II ended, Planck, his second wife, and their son were brought to a relative in Göttingen, where Planck died on 4 October 1947.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He is buried in the Stadtfriedhof in Göttingen.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was a member of the Lutheran Church in Germany.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He was very tolerant toward alternative views and religions.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He criticized atheism for being focused on the derision of such symbols, while at the same time warned of the over-estimation of the importance of such symbols by believers.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck said in 1944, "As a man who has devoted his whole life to the most clear headed science, to the study of matter, I can tell you as a result of my research about atoms this much: There is no matter as such.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] All matter originates and exists only by virtue of a force which brings the particle of an atom to vibration and holds this most minute solar system of the atom together.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] We must assume behind this force the existence of a conscious and intelligent spirit [orig.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck argued that the concept of God is important to both religion and science, but in different ways: "Both religion and science require a belief in God.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] For believers, God is in the beginning, and for physicists He is at the end of all considerations … To the former He is the foundation, to the latter, the crown of the edifice of every generalized world view".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Heilbron characterized Planck's views on God as deistic.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Heilbron further relates that when asked about his religious affiliation, Planck replied that although he had always been deeply religious, he did not believe "in a personal God, let alone a Christian God".
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] While Planck began his career as a proponent of Ernst Mach's positivism, his discovery of the quantum of action led him to embrace scientific realism.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He argued that the "world-picture" of physics must be based on objective realities that exist independently of human observation.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] This philosophical stance led to a famous public rift with Mach in 1908.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck's belief in an objective, causal universe defined by "absolutes" was a major factor in his early and unwavering support for Einstein's theory of relativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] However, this same realism later made him a prominent critic of the probabilistic nature of the Copenhagen interpretation championed by Niels Bohr.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck was an accomplished musician who possessed absolute pitch.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] He was a pianist, organist, and cellist who composed the opera *Die Liebe im Walde* during his university years.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Throughout his life, his home in Berlin became a cultural hub where he hosted weekly musical soirées.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] These gatherings frequently included Albert Einstein on the violin and the renowned violinist Joseph Joachim.
[src:thermodynamicist/max-planck] Planck once noted that the laws of physics and the laws of harmony both represented different paths to understanding universal absolutes.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Theoretical expositions of this branch of physics have their origins in Ancient Greece, for instance, in the writings of Aristotle and Archimedes (see History of classical mechanics and Timeline of classical mechanics).
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] During the early modern period, scientists such as Galileo Galilei, Johannes Kepler, Christiaan Huygens, and Isaac Newton laid the foundation for what is now known as classical mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] In the 20th century the concepts of classical mechanics were challenged by new discoveries, leading to fundamentally new approaches including relativistic mechanics and quantum mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The ancient Greek philosophers were among the first to propose that abstract principles govern nature.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The main theory of mechanics in antiquity was Aristotelian mechanics, though an alternative theory is exposed in the pseudo-Aristotelian *Mechanical Problems*, often attributed to one of his successors.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] There is another tradition that goes back to the ancient Greeks where mathematics is used more extensively to analyze bodies statically or dynamically, an approach that may have been stimulated by prior work of the Pythagorean Archytas.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Examples of this tradition include pseudo-Euclid (*On the Balance*), Archimedes (*On the Equilibrium of Planes*, *On Floating Bodies*), Hero (*Mechanica*), and Pappus (*Collection*, Book VIII).
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] In the Middle Ages, Aristotle's theories were criticized and modified by a number of figures, beginning with John Philoponus in the 6th century.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] A central problem was that of projectile motion, which was discussed by Hipparchus and Philoponus.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Persian Islamic polymath Ibn Sīnā published his theory of motion in *The Book of Healing* (1020).
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] He said that an impetus is imparted to a projectile by the thrower, and viewed it as persistent, requiring external forces such as air resistance to dissipate it.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Ibn Sina made a distinction between 'force' and 'inclination' (called "mayl"), and argued that an object gained mayl when the object is in opposition to its natural motion.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] So he concluded that continuation of motion is attributed to the inclination that is transferred to the object, and that object will be in motion until the mayl is spent.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] He also claimed that a projectile in a vacuum would not stop unless it is acted upon, consistent with Newton's first law of motion.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] On the question of a body subject to a constant (uniform) force, the 12th-century Jewish scholar Hibat Allah Abu'l-Barakat al-Baghdaadi says that acceleration of a falling body was a consequence of continuous action of the bodies natural inclination.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Influenced by earlier writers such as Ibn Sina and al-Baghdaadi, the 14th-century French priest Jean Buridan developed the theory of impetus, which later developed into the modern theories of inertia, velocity, acceleration and momentum.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] This work and others were developed in 14th-century England by the Oxford Calculators such as Thomas Bradwardine, who studied and formulated various laws regarding falling bodies.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The concept that the main properties of a body are uniformly accelerated motion (as of falling bodies) was worked out by the 14th-century Oxford Calculators.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Two central figures in the early modern age are Galileo Galilei and Isaac Newton.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Galileo's final statement of his mechanics, particularly of falling bodies, is his *Two New Sciences* (1638).
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Newton's 1687 *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica* provided a detailed mathematical account of mechanics, using the newly developed mathematics of calculus and providing the basis of Newtonian mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] There is some dispute over the priority of various ideas: Newton's *Principia* is certainly the seminal work and has been tremendously influential, and many of the mathematical results therein could not have been stated earlier without the development of the calculus.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] However, many of the ideas, particularly as they pertain to inertia and falling bodies, had been developed by prior scholars such as Christiaan Huygens and the less-known medieval predecessors.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Assigning precise credit is difficult, since scientific language and standards of proof have changed; the ideas of medieval scholars may be regarded either as equivalent to modern statements or merely as preliminary hypotheses similar to them.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Two main modern developments in mechanics are general relativity of Einstein, and quantum mechanics, both developed in the 20th century based in part on earlier 19th-century ideas.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The development in the modern continuum mechanics, particularly in the areas of elasticity, plasticity, fluid dynamics, electrodynamics, and thermodynamics of deformable media, started in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The often-used term *body* needs to stand for a wide assortment of objects, including particles, projectiles, spacecraft, stars, parts of machinery, parts of solids, parts of fluids (gases and liquids), etc.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Other distinctions between the various sub-disciplines of mechanics concern the nature of the bodies being described.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Particles are bodies with little (known) internal structure, treated as mathematical points in classical mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Rigid bodies have size and shape, but retain a simplicity close to that of the particle, adding just a few so-called degrees of freedom, such as orientation in space.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Otherwise, bodies may be semi-rigid, i.e. elastic, or non-rigid, i.e. fluid.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] These subjects have both classical and quantum divisions of study.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] For instance, the motion of a spacecraft, regarding its orbit and attitude (rotation), is described by the relativistic theory of classical mechanics, while the analogous movements of an atomic nucleus are described by quantum mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The following are the three main designations consisting of various subjects that are studied in mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Note that there is also the "theory of fields" which constitutes a separate discipline in physics, formally treated as distinct from mechanics, whether it be classical fields or quantum fields.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] But in actual practice, subjects belonging to mechanics and fields are closely interwoven.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Thus, for instance, forces that act on particles are frequently derived from fields (electromagnetic or gravitational), and particles generate fields by acting as sources.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] In fact, in quantum mechanics, particles themselves are fields, as described theoretically by the wave function.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Historically, classical mechanics had been around for nearly a quarter millennium before quantum mechanics developed.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Classical mechanics originated with Isaac Newton's laws of motion in Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica, developed over the seventeenth century.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Quantum mechanics developed later, over the nineteenth century, precipitated by Planck's postulate and Albert Einstein's explanation of the photoelectric effect.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Both fields are commonly held to constitute the most certain knowledge that exists about physical nature.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Classical mechanics has especially often been viewed as a model for other so-called exact sciences.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Essential in this respect is the extensive use of mathematics in theories, as well as the decisive role played by experiment in generating and testing them.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Quantum mechanics is of a bigger scope, as it encompasses classical mechanics as a sub-discipline which applies under certain restricted circumstances.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] According to the correspondence principle, there is no contradiction or conflict between the two subjects, each simply pertains to specific situations.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Quantum mechanics has superseded classical mechanics at the foundation level and is indispensable for the explanation and prediction of processes at the molecular, atomic, and sub-atomic level.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] However, for macroscopic processes classical mechanics is able to solve problems which are unmanageably difficult (mainly due to computational limits) in quantum mechanics and hence remains useful and well used.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Modern descriptions of such behavior begin with a careful definition of such quantities as displacement (distance moved), time, velocity, acceleration, mass, and force.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Until about 400 years ago, however, motion was explained from a very different point of view.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Often cited as father to modern science, Galileo brought together the ideas of other great thinkers of his time and began to calculate motion in terms of distance travelled from some starting position and the time that it took.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] He showed that the speed of falling objects increases steadily during the time of their fall.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] This acceleration is the same for heavy objects as for light ones, provided air friction (air resistance) is discounted.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The English mathematician and physicist Isaac Newton improved this analysis by defining force and mass and relating these to acceleration.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] For everyday phenomena, however, Newton's three laws of motion remain the cornerstone of dynamics, which is the study of what causes motion.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] Akin to the distinction between quantum and classical mechanics, Albert Einstein's general and special theories of relativity have expanded the scope of Newton and Galileo's formulation of mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] The differences between relativistic and Newtonian mechanics become significant and even dominant as the velocity of a body approaches the speed of light.
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] For instance, in Newtonian mechanics, the kinetic energy of a free particle is *E* = ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2, whereas in relativistic mechanics, it is *E* = (*γ* − 1)*mc*2 (where *γ* is the Lorentz factor; this formula reduces to the Newtonian expression in the low energy limit).
[src:thermodynamicist/mechanics] For high-energy processes, quantum mechanics must be adjusted to account for special relativity; this has led to the development of quantum field theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's scientific work attracted little attention during his lifetime, but in 1834 it became the object of a detailed commentary and explanation by another French engineer, Émile Clapeyron.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Clapeyron's commentary in turn attracted the attention of William Thomson (later Lord Kelvin) and Rudolf Clausius.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Thomson used Carnot's analysis to develop an absolute thermodynamic temperature scale, while Clausius used it to define the concept of entropy, thus formalizing the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot was the son of Lazare Carnot, an eminent mathematician, engineer, and commander of the French Revolutionary Army and later of the Napoleonic army.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Some of the difficulties that Carnot faced in his own career might have been connected to the persecution of his family by the restored Bourbon monarchy after the fall of Napoleon in 1815.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot died in relative obscurity at the age of 36, but today he is often characterized as the "father of thermodynamics".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Sadi Carnot was born in Paris on 1 June 1796, at the Petit Luxembourg palace, where his father Lazare resided as one of the five members of the Directory, the highest governing body of the French First Republic in the immediate aftermath of the Thermidorian Reaction.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] His mother, Sophie *née* Dupont (1764-1813), came from a wealthy family based in Saint-Omer.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's father Lazare named him after the 13th-century Persian poet Sadi of Shiraz.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] An elder brother, also named Sadi, had been born in 1794 but died in infancy the following year.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] "Sadi" is the only given name that appears in the second-born's civil birth certificate, dated 14 prairial, year IV in the French Republican calendar.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] On 11 July 1796, the child was baptized in the Catholic church of Saint-Louis-d'Antin as "Nicolas-Léonard Dupont".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] The principal witness at that baptism was his maternal grandfather, Jacques-Antoine-Léonard Dupont.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] The father is wrongly identified in the baptismal record as Jacques-Léonard-Joseph-Auguste Dupont (who was, in fact, the child's maternal uncle).
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Following the biographical notice published long after his death by his brother Hippolyte, most sources now give his full name as "Nicolas Léonard Sadi", but there is no evidence that he ever used any name other than "Sadi".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot had a younger brother, Hippolyte Carnot, who was born in 1801 in Saint-Omer and who would later become a prominent politician.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Hippolyte's eldest son Marie François Sadi Carnot served as President of France from 1887 to 1894.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Another of Hippolyte's sons was the chemist, mining engineer and politician Adolphe Carnot.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot himself would remain a bachelor and left no descendants.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] The young Carnot was educated first at home by his father and later at the Lycée Charlemagne, in Paris, where he prepared for the examinations required to enter the École polytechnique, which his father had helped to establish.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In 1811, at the age of 16 (the minimum allowed), Carnot became a cadet of the École polytechnique, where his classmates included the future mathematician Michel Chasles.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Among his professors were André-Marie Ampère, Siméon Denis Poisson, François Arago, and Gaspard-Gustave Coriolis.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Thus, the school had become renowned for its instruction in mathematics and physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] During the Battle of Paris in March of 1814, Carnot, Chasles, and other cadets of the École polytechnique participated in the defense of Vincennes.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This appears to have been Carnot's only experience of battle.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot graduated in 1814 and was admitted at the École d'application de l'artillerie et du génie ("School of Applied Artillery and Military Engineering") in Metz, where he completed a two-year course.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot then became an officer in the French army's corps of engineers.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's father Lazare served as Napoleon's minister of the interior during the "Hundred Days", and, after Napoleon's final defeat in 1815, Lazare was forced into exile in the German city of Magdeburg.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's position in the army, under the restored Bourbon monarchy of King Louis XVIII, became increasingly difficult.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Lazare never returned to France, dying in Magdeburg in 1823.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot became a captain in the *Génie* and was posted to various locations, where he inspected fortifications, tracked plans, and wrote many reports.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] However, it appeared that his recommendations were ignored and that his career was stagnating.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] On 15 September 1818, at the age of 22, he took a six-month leave to prepare for the entrance examination to the newly formed General Staff in Paris.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot passed the exam and joined the General Staff in January 1819, with the lower rank of lieutenant.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] He remained on call for military duty, but from then on he dedicated most of his attention to private intellectual pursuits and received only two-thirds pay.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In Paris, Carnot befriended Nicolas Clément and Charles-Bernard Desormes and attended lectures on physics and chemistry at the Sorbonne and the Collège de France.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] He also attended the Conservatoire national des arts et métiers, where he followed the lectures on chemistry by Clément and those on economics by Jean-Baptiste Say.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot became interested in understanding the limits to improving the performance of steam engines, which led him to the investigations that became his *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire*, published at his own expense in June 1824.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot was finally promoted to his former rank of captain in September of 1827, but the following April he quit the army, having completed only fifteen months of active service and without right to a pension.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In a directory of alumni of the École polytechnique published by Ambroise Fourcy in 1828, Carnot is listed as "maker of steam engines".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This and some other indications suggest that Carnot may have been involved in a practical scheme for the improvement of steam engines, but no patents or other concrete evidences of that work have emerged.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot was interested in political economy.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] His political orientation was liberal, but he seems to have preferred the more interventionist doctrines of Jean de Sismondi to the *laissez-faire* policies advocated by classical liberal economists such as Say and David Ricardo.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Out of Carnot's private writings on economics, only some fragmentary notes survive.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot initially welcomed the July Revolution of 1830, which ended the Bourbonic regime under Charles X and established a new constitutional monarchy under "Citizen King" Louis Philippe.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] According to his brother Hippolyte, there was some discussion among leaders of the new regime of incorporating Sadi to the Chamber of Peers, as he could be considered to have inherited the Imperial title of "Count Carnot" that Napoleon had bestowed on his father Lazare in 1815.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Nothing came of this, however, perhaps because Sadi's republican convictions prevented him from accepting a hereditary distinction.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] According to recollections published long after Carnot's death by his brother Hippolyte, Carnot was an avid reader of Blaise Pascal, Molière and Jean de La Fontaine.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Hippolyte recalled that Carnot was a philosophical theist who believed in divine causality but not in divine punishment.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot wrote in his private papers that "what to an ignorant man is chance, cannot be chance to one better instructed".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] He was critical of established religion, but spoke in favor of "the belief in an all-powerful Being, who loves us and watches over us".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Hippolyte also described his brother as a talented violin player, interested principally in the music of Jean-Baptiste Lully and Giovanni Battista Viotti, who also cultivated gymnastics, fencing, swimming, dancing, and skating.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] According to historian of science James F.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Challey, "although sensitive and perceptive", Carnot "appeared extremely introverted, even aloof, to all but a few close friends".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This may help explain why Carnot's work failed to make any significant impression within either the scientific or the engineering community during his lifetime.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In the summer of 1832 Carnot apparently suffered from a severe bout of scarlet fever.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] On 3 August, he was interned in a private sanatorium run by psychiatrist Jean-Étienne Esquirol and located in Ivry, just south of Paris.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] According to the hospital record, he was cured from "mania" but then died of cholera on 24 August.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot was buried in the old cemetery of Ivry, close to what is now the Mairie d'Ivry station.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] The work attracted little attention during his lifetime and virtually disappeared from booksellers and libraries.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Thomas Newcomen invented the first practical piston-operated steam engine in 1712.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Some 50 years after that, James Watt made his celebrated improvements, which were responsible for greatly increasing the usefulness of steam engines.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] When Carnot became interested in the subject in the 1820s, steam engines were in increasingly wide application in industry and their economic importance was widely recognized.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] That practical work on steam engines and the intuitive understanding among engineers of some of the principles underlying their operation co-existed, however, with an almost complete lack of a scientific understanding of the physical phenomena associated with heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] The principle of conservation of energy had not yet been clearly articulated and the ideas surrounding it were fragmentary and controversial.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot himself accepted the view, prevalent in France and associated with the work of Antoine Lavoisier, that heat is a weightless and invisible fluid, called "caloric", which may be liberated by chemical reactions and which flows from bodies at higher temperature to bodies at lower temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In his book, Carnot sought to answer basic questions: "Is there a limit to the work that can be generated from a given heat source?" and "Can the performance of an engine be improved by replacing steam with a different working fluid?".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Engineers in Carnot's time had tried, using highly pressurized steam and other fluids, to improve the efficiency of engines.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In these early stages of engine development, the efficiency of a typical engine – the useful work it was able to do when a given quantity of fuel was burned – was only about 5–7%.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's book was only 118 pages long and covered a wide range of topics about heat engines in what Carnot must have intended to be a form accessible to a wide public.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] He made minimal use of mathematics, which he confined to elementary algebra and arithmetic, except in some footnotes.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot discussed the relative merits of air and steam as working fluids, the merits of various aspects of steam-engine design, and even included some ideas of his own regarding possible practical improvements.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] However, the central part of the book was an abstract treatment of an idealized engine (the Carnot cycle) with which the author sought to clarify the fundamental principles that govern all heat engines, independently of the details of their design or operation.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This resulted in an idealized thermodynamic system upon which exact calculations could be made, and avoided the complications introduced by many of the crude features of the contemporary steam engines.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot considered an idealized process in which heat from a thermal reservoir at a high temperature flows very slowly (and thus reversibly) into the gas contained in a cylinder enclosed by a movable piston.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This gives an isothermal expansion of the gas that pushes out the piston and can be used to perform useful work.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This does not yet constitute an engine because the piston must be returned to its original position in order for the machine to run cyclically.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot then proposed reducing the temperature of the gas by an adiabatic expansion, during which the cylinder is thermally isolated so as to prevent heat from entering or leaving the gas.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Once the temperature of the gas has reached the same value as that of the colder reservoir, the cylinder is put into thermal contact with that reservoir and the gas undergoes an isothermal compression, during which it very slowly (and thus reversibly) rejects heat into the reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] To close the cycle, the temperature of the gas in the cylinder can be raised by adiabatic compression, until it reaches a value equal to the temperature of the hotter reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This succession of isothermal expansion, adiabatic expansion, isothermal compression, and adiabatic compression can then be repeated as many times as desired, generating a net amount of work each time, at the expense of a transfer of heat from the hotter reservoir to the colder reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] As Carnot explained, such a cycle constitutes the most efficient heat engine possible (given the temperatures of the two reservoirs).
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This is partly because of the (trivial) absence of friction, heat leakage, or other incidental wasteful processes, but mainly because it involves no conduction of heat between parts of the engine at different temperatures.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot understood that the conduction of heat between bodies at different temperatures is a wasteful and irreversible process, which must be minimized if the heat engine is to achieve its maximum efficiency.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Because Carnot's cycle is reversible, it can also be used as a refrigerator: if an external agent supplies the needed mechanical work to move the piston, the sequence of transformations of the gas will absorb heat from the colder reservoir and reject it into the hotter reservoir.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot argued that no engine operating between reservoirs at two given temperatures could deliver more work than his reversible cycle.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Otherwise, the more efficient engine could run Carnot's cycle in reverse as a refrigerator, thus returning all of the "caloric" from the colder back to the hotter reservoir, with some positive amount of work left over to perform a further useful task.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot assumed that such a process, in which no net "caloric" was consumed while positive work could be done forever, would be a perpetual motion and therefore forbidden by the laws of physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Later in his book, Carnot considered a heat engine operating very close to the boiling point of water, alcohol, or some other working fluid.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] The transition between the liquid and vapor phases involves a sudden change in density (and therefore in the volume occupied by the fluid) while a latent heat is needed to transform some amount of the fluid from one phase to the other as the temperature stays constant.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This is modernly called a first-order phase transition.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] By requiring that the volume change associated with such a transition not be available to construct what he characterized as a perpetual motion device, Carnot arrived at what would later be formalized mathematically as the "Clausius–Clapeyron relation".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In the *Feynman Lectures on Physics*, theoretical physicist Richard Feynman stresses that this result is due to Carnot and gives a modernized version of Carnot's original argument.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] James Thomson's prediction was later confirmed experimentally by his brother William Thomson (the future Lord Kelvin), who found that the data agreed fully with Carnot's analysis.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot published his book in June 1824, and it was presented at that time to the French Academy of Sciences by Pierre-Simon Girard.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Girard also published a praiseful but rather broad review of the book in the *Revue encyclopédique*, but after that the book seems to have fallen into obscurity.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] It was only after the publication of an extensive commentary and explication of Carnot's work by Émile Clapeyron in 1834 that engineers and scientists began to take an interest in Carnot's contributions.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Clapeyron's article was translated into English in 1837 and into German in 1843.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] William Thomson read Clapeyron's paper in 1845, while visiting the Paris laboratory of Henri Regnault, but it was only at the end of 1848 that Thomson was able to read Carnot's original work, in a copy provided to him by Lewis Gordon.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Independently of Thomson, the German physicist Rudolf Clausius also based his study of thermodynamics on Carnot's work.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Clausius modified Carnot's arguments to make them compatible with the mechanical equivalence of heat.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] This then led Clausius to define the concept of entropy and to formulate the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's text was re-printed in 1871 in the *Annales Scientifiques* of the École normale supérieure, and again by Gauthier-Villars in 1878 with the collaboration of Hippolyte Carnot.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] An English translation of the book was published in 1890 by R.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] That version has been reprinted in recent decades by Dover.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In 1892, Lord Kelvin referred to Carnot's essay as "an epoch-making gift to science".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot published his book in the heyday of steam engines.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] His theory explained the advantage of engines that use superheated steam, since they absorb heat from a reservoir at a higher temperature.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's work did not, however, lead to any immediate practical improvements of steam technologies.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] It was only towards the end of the nineteenth century that engineers deliberately implemented Carnot's key concepts: that the efficiency of a heat is improved by increasing the temperature at which heat is drawn and by minimizing the flow of heat between bodies at different temperatures.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot's younger brother Hippolyte obscured the details of Carnot's death and destroyed most of his personal papers.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] These are the only sources of information on many aspects of Carnot's life and thought.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In the opinion of historian of science Arthur Birembaut, the "smokescreen" that Hippolyte drew over his brother's life makes it impossible now to reconstruct the details of Carnot's career, his relationship with other physicists and engineers, and the circumstances of his death.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Among the private notes published by Hippolyte in 1878, there is material indicating that Carnot had, by the spring of 1832, rejected the caloric theory and accepted the equivalence of heat and work.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In those same notes, Carnot estimated that 1 kilocalorie is the equivalent of 370 kg·m, whereas the currently accepted value is 427 kg·m.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Carnot did not, however, publish any of that work.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] It is possible that his uncertainty about the consequences for the validity of his previous analysis in the *Reflections* of rejecting the caloric theory might explain why he did not follow up on his work of 1824 before his untimely death.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] Following the work of Kelvin and Clausius, Carnot came to be widely regarded as the "father of thermodynamics".
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In 1970, the International Astronomical Union named the lunar crater Carnot in his honor.
[src:thermodynamicist/nicolas-léonard-sadi-carnot] In 1991, the minor planet 12289 was also named after Carnot.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics is one of the oldest academic disciplines.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Over much of the past two millennia, physics, chemistry, biology, and certain branches of mathematics were part of natural philosophy, but during the Scientific Revolution in the 17th century, these natural sciences branched into separate research endeavors.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics intersects with many interdisciplinary areas of research, such as biophysics and quantum chemistry, and the boundaries of physics are not rigidly defined.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] New ideas in physics often explain the fundamental mechanisms studied by other sciences and suggest new avenues of research in these and other academic disciplines, such as mathematics and philosophy.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Advances in physics often enable new technologies.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The word *physics* comes from the Latin *physica* ('study of nature'), which itself is a borrowing of the Greek φυσική (*phusikḗ* 'natural science'), a term derived from φύσις (*phúsis* 'origin, nature, property').
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Astronomy is one of the oldest natural sciences.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Early civilizations dating before 3000 BCE, such as the Sumerians, ancient Egyptians, and the Indus Valley Civilization, had a predictive knowledge and a basic awareness of the motions of the Sun, Moon, and stars.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The stars and planets, believed to represent gods, were often worshipped.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] While the explanations for the observed positions of the stars were often unscientific and lacking in evidence, these early observations laid the foundation for later astronomy, as the stars were found to traverse great circles across the sky, which could not explain the positions of the planets.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] According to Asger Aaboe, the origins of Western astronomy can be found in Mesopotamia, and all Western efforts in the exact sciences are descended from late Babylonian astronomy.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Natural philosophy has its origins in Greece during the Archaic period (650 BCE – 480 BCE), when pre-Socratic philosophers like Thales rejected non-naturalistic explanations for natural phenomena and proclaimed that every event had a natural cause.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] They proposed ideas verified by reason and observation, and many of their hypotheses proved successful in experiment; for example, atomism was found to be correct approximately 2000 years after it was proposed by Leucippus and his pupil Democritus.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] During the classical period in Greece (6th, 5th and 4th centuries BCE) and in Hellenistic times, natural philosophy developed along many lines of inquiry.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Aristotle (Greek: Ἀριστοτέλης, *Aristotélēs*) (384–322 BCE), a student of Plato, wrote on many subjects, including a substantial treatise on "Physics" – in the 4th century BC.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Aristotelian physics was influential for about two millennia.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] His approach mixed some limited observation with logical deductive arguments, but did not rely on experimental verification of deduced statements.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Aristotle's foundational work in Physics, though very imperfect, formed a framework against which later thinkers further developed the field.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] His approach is entirely superseded today.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] He explained ideas such as motion (and gravity) with the theory of four elements.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Aristotle believed that each of the four classical elements (air, fire, water, earth) had its own natural place.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Because of their differing densities, each element will revert to its own specific place in the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] So, because of their weights, fire would be at the top, air underneath fire, then water, then lastly earth.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] He also stated that when a small amount of one element enters the natural place of another, the less abundant element will automatically go towards its own natural place.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For example, if there is a fire on the ground, the flames go up into the air in an attempt to go back into its natural place where it belongs.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] His laws of motion included: that heavier objects will fall faster, the speed being proportional to the weight and the speed of the object that is falling depends inversely on the density object it is falling through (e.g. density of air).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] He also stated that, when it comes to violent motion (motion of an object when a force is applied to it by a second object), the speed that object moves will only be as fast or strong as the measure of force applied to it.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The problem of motion and its causes was studied carefully, leading to the philosophical notion of a "prime mover" as the ultimate source of all motion in the world (Book 8 of his treatise *Physics*).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The Western Roman Empire fell to invaders and internal decay in the fifth century, resulting in a decline in intellectual pursuits in western Europe.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] By contrast, the Eastern Roman Empire (usually known as the Byzantine Empire) resisted the attacks from invaders and continued to advance various fields of learning, including physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In the sixth century, John Philoponus challenged the dominant Aristotelian approach to science although much of his work was focused on Christian theology.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In the sixth century, Isidore of Miletus created an important compilation of Archimedes' works that are copied in the Archimedes Palimpsest.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Islamic scholarship inherited Aristotelian physics from the Greeks and during the Islamic Golden Age developed it further.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The most notable innovations under Islamic scholarship were in the field of optics and vision, which came from the works of many scientists like Ibn Sahl, Al-Kindi, Ibn al-Haytham, Al-Farisi and Avicenna.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In his Book of Optics (also known as Kitāb al-Manāẓir) Ibn al-Haytham presented the idea of light rays as an alternative to the ancient Greek idea about visual rays.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Like Ptolemy, Ibn al-Haytham applied controlled experiments, verifying the laws of refraction and reflection with the new concept of light rays, but still lacking the concept of image formation.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics became a separate science when early modern Europeans used experimental and quantitative methods to discover what are now considered to be the laws of physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Newton, and separately Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, developed calculus, the mathematical study of continuous change, and Newton applied it to solve physical problems.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The discovery of laws in thermodynamics, chemistry, and electromagnetics resulted from research efforts during the Industrial Revolution as energy needs increased.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] By the end of the 19th century, theories of thermodynamics, mechanics, and electromagnetics matched a wide variety of observations.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Taken together these theories became the basis for what would later be called classical physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] A few experimental results remained inexplicable.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Classical electromagnetism presumed a medium, an luminiferous aether to support the propagation of waves, but this medium could not be detected.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The intensity of light from hot glowing blackbody objects did not match the predictions of thermodynamics and electromagnetism.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The character of electron emission of illuminated metals differed from predictions.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] These failures, seemingly insignificant in the big picture would upset the physics world in first two decades of the 20th century.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Modern physics began in the early 20th century with the work of Max Planck in quantum theory and Albert Einstein's theory of relativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Both of these theories came about due to inaccuracies in classical mechanics in certain situations.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Classical mechanics predicted that the speed of light depends on the motion of the observer, which could not be resolved with the constant speed predicted by Maxwell's equations of electromagnetism.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] This discrepancy was corrected by Einstein's theory of special relativity, which replaced classical mechanics for fast-moving bodies and allowed for a constant speed of light.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Black-body radiation provided another problem for classical physics, which was corrected when Planck proposed that the excitation of material oscillators is possible only in discrete steps proportional to their frequency.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] This, along with the photoelectric effect and a complete theory predicting discrete energy levels of electron orbitals, led to the theory of quantum mechanics improving on classical physics at very small scales.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Quantum mechanics would come to be pioneered by Werner Heisenberg, Erwin Schrödinger and Paul Dirac.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] From this early work, and work in related fields, the Standard Model of particle physics was derived.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Areas of mathematics in general are important to this field, such as the study of probabilities and groups.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics deals with a wide variety of systems, although certain theories are used by all physicists.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Each of these theories was experimentally tested numerous times and found to be an adequate approximation of nature.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] These central theories are important tools for research into more specialized topics, and any physicist, regardless of their specialization, is expected to be literate in them.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] These include classical mechanics, quantum mechanics, thermodynamics and statistical mechanics, electromagnetism, and special relativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In the first decades of the 20th century physics was revolutionized by the discoveries of quantum mechanics and relativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The changes were so fundamental that these new concepts became the foundation of "modern physics", with other topics becoming "classical physics".
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The majority of applications of physics are essentially classical.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The laws of classical physics accurately describe systems whose important length scales are greater than the atomic scale and whose motions are much slower than the speed of light.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Outside of this domain, observations do not match predictions provided by classical mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Classical physics includes the traditional branches and topics that were recognized and well-developed before the beginning of the 20th century—classical mechanics, thermodynamics, and electromagnetism.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Acoustics is the study of how sound is produced, controlled, transmitted and received.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Important modern branches of acoustics include ultrasonics, the study of sound waves of very high frequency beyond the range of human hearing; bioacoustics, the physics of animal calls and hearing; and electroacoustics, the manipulation of audible sound waves using electronics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Optics, the study of light, is concerned not only with visible light but also with infrared and ultraviolet radiation, which exhibit all of the phenomena of visible light except visibility, e.g., reflection, refraction, interference, diffraction, dispersion, and polarization of light.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Heat is a form of energy, the internal energy possessed by the particles of which a substance is composed; thermodynamics deals with the relationships between heat and other forms of energy.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Electricity and magnetism have been studied as a single branch of physics since the intimate connection between them was discovered in the early 19th century; an electric current gives rise to a magnetic field, and a changing magnetic field induces an electric current.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Electrostatics deals with electric charges at rest, electrodynamics with moving charges, and magnetostatics with magnetic poles at rest.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The discovery of relativity and of quantum mechanics in the first decades of the 20th century transformed the conceptual basis of physics without reducing the practical value of most of the physical theories developed up to that time.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Consequently the topics of physics have come to be divided into "classical physics" and "modern physics", with the latter category including effects related to quantum mechanics and relativity.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Classical physics is generally concerned with matter and energy on the normal scale of observation, while much of modern physics is concerned with the behavior of matter and energy under extreme conditions or on a very large or very small scale.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For example, atomic and nuclear physics study matter on the smallest scale at which chemical elements can be identified.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The physics of elementary particles is on an even smaller scale since it is concerned with the most basic units of matter; this branch of physics is also known as high-energy physics because of the extremely high energies necessary to produce many types of particles in particle accelerators.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] On this scale, ordinary, commonsensical notions of space, time, matter, and energy are no longer valid.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The two chief theories of modern physics present a different picture of the concepts of space, time, and matter from that presented by classical physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Classical mechanics approximates nature as continuous, while quantum theory is concerned with the discrete nature of many phenomena at the atomic and subatomic level and with the complementary aspects of particles and waves in the description of such phenomena.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Both quantum theory and the theory of relativity find applications in many areas of modern physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physicists use the scientific method to test the validity of a physical theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] By using a methodical approach to compare the implications of a theory with the conclusions drawn from its related experiments and observations, physicists are better able to test the validity of a theory in a logical, unbiased, and repeatable way.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] To that end, experiments are performed and observations are made in order to determine the validity or invalidity of a theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] A scientific law is a concise verbal or mathematical statement of a relation that expresses a fundamental principle of some theory, such as Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Theorists seek to develop mathematical models that both agree with existing experiments and successfully predict future experimental results, while experimentalists devise and perform experiments to test theoretical predictions and explore new phenomena.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Although theory and experiment are developed separately, they strongly affect and depend upon each other.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physicists who work at the interplay of theory and experiment are called phenomenologists, who study complex phenomena observed in experiment and work to relate them to a fundamental theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Theoretical physics has historically taken inspiration from philosophy; electromagnetism was unified this way.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Beyond the known universe, the field of theoretical physics also deals with hypothetical issues, such as parallel universes, a multiverse, and higher dimensions.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Theorists invoke these ideas in hopes of solving particular problems with existing theories; they then explore the consequences of these ideas and work toward making testable predictions.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Experimental physics expands, and is expanded by, engineering and technology.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Experimental physicists who are involved in basic research design and perform experiments with equipment such as particle accelerators and lasers, whereas those involved in applied research often work in industry, developing technologies such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and transistors.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Feynman has noted that experimentalists may seek areas that have not been explored well by theorists.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics covers a wide range of phenomena, from elementary particles (such as quarks, neutrinos, and electrons) to the largest superclusters of galaxies.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Included in these phenomena are the most basic objects composing all other things.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Therefore, physics is sometimes called the "fundamental science".
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics aims to describe the various phenomena that occur in nature in terms of simpler phenomena.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Thus, physics aims to both connect the things observable to humans to root causes, and then connect these causes together.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For example, the ancient Chinese observed that certain rocks (lodestone and magnetite) were attracted to one another by an invisible force.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] This effect was later called magnetism, which was first rigorously studied in the 17th century.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] But even before the Chinese discovered magnetism, the ancient Greeks knew of other objects such as amber, that when rubbed with fur would cause a similar invisible attraction between the two.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] This was also first studied rigorously in the 17th century and came to be called electricity.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Thus, physics had come to understand two observations of nature in terms of some root cause (electricity and magnetism).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] However, further work in the 19th century revealed that these two forces were just two different aspects of one force—electromagnetism.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] This process of "unifying" forces continues today, and electromagnetism and the weak nuclear force are now considered to be two aspects of the electroweak interaction.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics hopes to find an ultimate reason (theory of everything) for why nature is as it is (see section *Current research* below for more information).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Research in physics is continually progressing on a large number of fronts.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In condensed matter physics, an important unsolved theoretical problem is that of high-temperature superconductivity.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Many condensed matter experiments are aiming to fabricate workable spintronics and quantum computers.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In particle physics, the first pieces of experimental evidence for physics beyond the Standard Model have begun to appear.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Foremost among these are indications that neutrinos have non-zero mass.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] These experimental results appear to have solved the long-standing solar neutrino problem, and the physics of massive neutrinos remains an area of active theoretical and experimental research.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The Large Hadron Collider has already found the Higgs boson, but future research aims to prove or disprove the supersymmetry, which extends the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Research on the nature of the major mysteries of dark matter and dark energy is also currently ongoing.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Although much progress has been made in high-energy, quantum, and astronomical physics, many everyday phenomena involving complexity, chaos, or turbulence are still poorly understood.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] These complex phenomena have received growing attention since the 1970s for several reasons, including the availability of modern mathematical methods and computers, which enabled complex systems to be modeled in new ways.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Complex physics has become part of increasingly interdisciplinary research, as exemplified by the study of turbulence in aerodynamics and the observation of pattern formation in biological systems.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The major fields of physics, along with their subfields and the theories and concepts they employ, are shown in the following table.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Since the 20th century, the individual fields of physics have become increasingly specialized, and today most physicists work in a single field for their entire careers.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] "Universalists" such as Einstein (1879–1955) and Lev Landau (1908–1968), who worked in multiple fields of physics, are now very rare.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Contemporary research in physics can be broadly divided into nuclear and particle physics; condensed matter physics; atomic, molecular, and optical physics; astrophysics; and applied physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Some physics departments also support physics education research and physics outreach.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Particle physics is the study of the elementary constituents of matter and energy and the interactions between them.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In addition, particle physicists design and develop the high-energy accelerators, detectors, and computer programs necessary for this research.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The field is also called "high-energy physics" because many elementary particles do not occur naturally but are created only during high-energy collisions of other particles.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Currently, the interactions of elementary particles and fields are described by the Standard Model.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The model accounts for the 12 known particles of matter (quarks and leptons) that interact via the strong, weak, and electromagnetic fundamental forces.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Dynamics are described in terms of matter particles exchanging gauge bosons (gluons, W and Z bosons, and photons, respectively).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The Standard Model also predicts a particle known as the Higgs boson.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In July 2012 CERN, the European laboratory for particle physics, announced the detection of a particle consistent with the Higgs boson, an integral part of the Higgs mechanism.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Nuclear physics is the field of physics that studies the constituents and interactions of atomic nuclei.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Atomic, molecular, and optical physics (AMO) is the study of matter—matter and light—matter interactions on the scale of single atoms and molecules.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The three areas are grouped together because of their interrelationships, the similarity of methods used, and the commonality of their relevant energy scales.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] All three areas include both classical, semi-classical and quantum treatments; they can treat their subject from a microscopic view (in contrast to a macroscopic view).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Atomic physics studies the electron shells of atoms.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Current research focuses on activities in quantum control, cooling and trapping of atoms and ions, low-temperature collision dynamics and the effects of electron correlation on structure and dynamics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Atomic physics is influenced by the nucleus (see hyperfine splitting), but intra-nuclear phenomena such as fission and fusion are considered part of nuclear physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Molecular physics focuses on multi-atomic structures and their internal and external interactions with matter and light.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Optical physics is distinct from optics in that it tends to focus not on the control of classical light fields by macroscopic objects but on the fundamental properties of optical fields and their interactions with matter in the microscopic realm.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Condensed matter physics is the field of physics that deals with the macroscopic physical properties of matter.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In particular, it is concerned with the "condensed" phases that appear whenever the number of particles in a system is extremely large and the interactions between them are strong.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The most familiar examples of condensed phases are solids and liquids, which arise from the bonding by way of the electromagnetic force between atoms.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Condensed matter physics is the largest field of contemporary physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Historically, condensed matter physics grew out of solid-state physics, which is now considered one of its main subfields.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The term *condensed matter physics* was apparently coined by Philip Anderson when he renamed his research group—previously *solid-state theory*—in 1967.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In 1978, the Division of Solid State Physics of the American Physical Society was renamed as the Division of Condensed Matter Physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Condensed matter physics has a large overlap with chemistry, materials science, nanotechnology and engineering.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Astrophysics and astronomy are the application of the theories and methods of physics to the study of stellar structure, stellar evolution, the origin of the Solar System, and related problems of cosmology.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Because astrophysics is a broad subject, astrophysicists typically apply many disciplines of physics, including mechanics, electromagnetism, statistical mechanics, thermodynamics, quantum mechanics, relativity, nuclear and particle physics, and atomic and molecular physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The discovery by Karl Jansky in 1931 that radio signals were emitted by celestial bodies initiated the science of radio astronomy.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Most recently, the frontiers of astronomy have been expanded by space exploration.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Perturbations and interference from the Earth's atmosphere make space-based observations necessary for infrared, ultraviolet, gamma-ray, and X-ray astronomy.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physical cosmology is the study of the formation and evolution of the universe on its largest scales.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Albert Einstein's theory of relativity plays a central role in all modern cosmological theories.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] In the early 20th century, Hubble's discovery that the universe is expanding, as shown by the Hubble diagram, prompted rival explanations known as the steady state universe and the Big Bang.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The Big Bang was confirmed by the success of Big Bang nucleosynthesis and the discovery of the cosmic microwave background in 1964.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The Big Bang model rests on two theoretical pillars: Albert Einstein's general relativity and the cosmological principle.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Cosmologists have recently established the ΛCDM model of the evolution of the universe, which includes cosmic inflation, dark energy, and dark matter.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics education or physics teaching refers to the education methods currently used to teach physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The occupation is called physics educator or physics teacher.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics education research refers to an area of pedagogical research that seeks to improve those methods.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Historically, physics has been taught at the high school and college level primarily by the lecture method together with laboratory exercises aimed at verifying concepts taught in the lectures.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] These concepts are better understood when lectures are accompanied with demonstration, hand-on experiments, and questions that require students to ponder what will happen in an experiment and why.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Students who participate in active learning for example with hands-on experiments learn through self-discovery.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] By trial and error they learn to change their preconceptions about phenomena in physics and discover the underlying concepts.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics education is part of the broader area of science education.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] A physicist is a scientist who specializes in the field of physics, which encompasses the interactions of matter and energy at all length and time scales in the physical universe.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physicists generally are interested in the root or ultimate causes of phenomena, and usually frame their understanding in mathematical terms.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] They work across a wide range of research fields, spanning all length scales: from sub-atomic and particle physics, through biological physics, to cosmological length scales encompassing the universe as a whole.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physicists can apply their knowledge towards solving practical problems or to developing new technologies (also known as applied physics or engineering physics).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics, as with the rest of science, relies on the philosophy of science and its "scientific method" to advance knowledge of the physical world.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The scientific method employs *a priori and a posteriori* reasoning as well as the use of Bayesian inference to measure the validity of a given theory.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Study of the philosophical issues surrounding physics, the philosophy of physics, involves issues such as the nature of space and time, determinism, and metaphysical outlooks such as empiricism, naturalism, and realism.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Many physicists have written about the philosophical implications of their work, for instance Laplace, who championed causal determinism, and Erwin Schrödinger, who wrote on quantum mechanics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The mathematical physicist Roger Penrose has been called a Platonist by Stephen Hawking, a view Penrose discusses in his book, *The Road to Reality*.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Hawking referred to himself as an "unashamed reductionist" and took issue with Penrose's views.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Mathematics provides a compact and exact language used to describe the order in nature.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] This was noted and advocated by Pythagoras, Plato, Galileo, and Newton.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Some theorists, like Hilary Putnam and Penelope Maddy, hold that logical truths, and therefore mathematical reasoning, depend on the empirical world.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] This is usually combined with the claim that the laws of logic express universal regularities found in the structural features of the world, which may explain the peculiar relation between these fields.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics uses mathematics to organize and formulate experimental results.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] From those results, precise or estimated solutions are obtained, or quantitative results, from which new predictions can be made and experimentally confirmed or negated.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The results from physics experiments are numerical data, with their units of measure and estimates of the errors in the measurements.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Technologies based on mathematics, like computation have made computational physics an active area of research.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Ontology is a prerequisite for physics, but not for mathematics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] It means physics is ultimately concerned with descriptions of the real world, while mathematics is concerned with abstract patterns, even beyond the real world.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Thus physics statements are synthetic, while mathematical statements are analytic.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Mathematics contains hypotheses, while physics contains theories.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Mathematics statements have to be only logically true, while predictions of physics statements must match observed and experimental data.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The distinction is clear-cut, but not always obvious.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For example, mathematical physics is the application of mathematics in physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Its methods are mathematical, but its subject is physical.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The problems in this field start with a "mathematical model of a physical situation" (system) and a "mathematical description of a physical law" that will be applied to that system.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Every mathematical statement used for solving has a hard-to-find physical meaning.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The final mathematical solution has an easier-to-find meaning, because it is what the solver is looking for.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics is a branch of fundamental science (also called basic science).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Physics is also called "*the* fundamental science" because all branches of natural science including chemistry, astronomy, geology, and biology are constrained by laws of physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Similarly, chemistry is often called the central science because of its role in linking the physical sciences.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For example, chemistry studies properties, structures, and reactions of matter (chemistry's focus on the molecular and atomic scale distinguishes it from physics).
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Structures are formed because particles exert electrical forces on each other, properties include physical characteristics of given substances, and reactions are bound by laws of physics, like conservation of energy, mass, and charge.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Fundamental physics seeks to better explain and understand phenomena in all spheres, without a specific practical application as a goal, other than the deeper insight into the phenomema themselves.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Applied physics is a general term for physics research and development that is intended for a particular use.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] An applied physics curriculum usually contains a few classes in an applied discipline, like geology or electrical engineering.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] It usually differs from engineering in that an applied physicist may not be designing something in particular, but rather is using physics or conducting physics research with the aim of developing new technologies or solving a problem.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The approach is similar to that of applied mathematics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] Applied physicists use physics in scientific research.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For instance, people working on accelerator physics might seek to build better particle detectors for research in theoretical physics.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For example, statics, a subfield of mechanics, is used in the building of bridges and other static structures.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] The understanding and use of acoustics results in sound control and better concert halls; similarly, the use of optics creates better optical devices.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] An understanding of physics makes for more realistic flight simulators, video games, and movies, and is often critical in forensic investigations.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] With the standard consensus that the laws of physics are universal and do not change with time, physics can be used to study things that would ordinarily be mired in uncertainty.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] For example, in the study of the origin of the Earth, a physicist can reasonably model Earth's mass, temperature, and rate of rotation, as a function of time allowing the extrapolation forward or backward in time and so predict future or prior events.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] It also allows for simulations in engineering that speed up the development of a new technology.
[src:thermodynamicist/physics] There is also considerable interdisciplinarity, so many other important fields are influenced by physics (e.g., the fields of econophysics and sociophysics).
[src:thermodynamicist/thermodynamicist] In thermodynamics, a **thermodynamicist** is someone who studies thermodynamic processes and phenomena, i.e. the physics that deal with mechanical action and relations of heat.
